        subjectDefinition: "The compound nucleus model proposes that nuclear reactions proceed in two independent stages. In Stage 1, the projectile is absorbed by the target nucleus, forming a highly excited intermediate state called the compound nucleus. The excitation energy is rapidly shared among all nucleons (within ~10⁻²² s) so that no nucleon retains memory of how the compound nucleus was formed. In Stage 2, the compound nucleus decays by emitting particles or gamma rays in a manner that depends only on its excitation energy, spin, and parity — not on how it was formed. This is the independence hypothesis: formation and decay are statistically independent.",

        results: "Bohr's model correctly predicted that the same compound nucleus could be produced via different reactions and would always decay with the same branching ratios regardless of the formation mechanism. The model also explained the resonance structure of cross-sections as arising from discrete excited states of the compound nucleus matching the total energy of projectile + target. Experimental confirmation came from studies showing that ⁶⁴Zn* produced by ⁶³Cu+p, ⁶⁰Ni+⁴He, and ⁶⁴Zn+γ all produced the same decay product distribution.",

        modernConnection: "Bohr's compound nucleus model remains a central framework in nuclear reaction theory today, applying whenever the projectile energy per nucleon is well below the nuclear binding energy and energy sharing among all nucleons is fast. The investigation below tests the independence hypothesis analytically: students compare predicted product distributions from different formation reactions leading to the same compound nucleus, and analyse branching ratios to verify or challenge the independence hypothesis.",

