                question: "Explain physically why the proton angular distribution in a (d,p) stripping reaction peaks at forward angles, while compound nucleus decay produces an isotropic or symmetric distribution in the centre-of-mass frame.",
                hint: "Consider the momentum transfer in each mechanism.",
                answer: "In compound nucleus decay, the system has forgotten all information about the beam direction by the time it decays — the angular momentum is distributed among all nucleons, and emission is isotropic (or symmetric about 90° in the CM frame) because all decay directions are equally probable for a thermalised system. In direct stripping, the interaction is a single fast collision: the deuteron passes the target nucleus, the neutron is stripped at the nuclear surface and absorbed, while the proton continues forward with most of the original beam momentum. The momentum transfer to the nucleus is small (only the neutron's half-momentum is deposited), so the proton retains most of its forward momentum. By conservation of momentum, the proton must emerge close to the beam direction — the angular distribution is peaked forward because the kinematics of single-step neutron transfer require it. The width and exact peak position are determined by the momentum transferred to the nucleus, which depends on the orbital angular momentum ℓ of the captured state."
