                hint: "KE_n ≈ E_d/4 in the CM frame for a deuteron split in half. Use R = 1.2 × 40^(1/3) fm.",
                answer: "CM kinetic energy for neutron: KE_n ≈ E_d × m_n/(m_d × 2) ≈ 10 × 1/(2×2) = 2.5 MeV. Neutron momentum: p_n = √(2 × 938.9 MeV/c² × 2.5 MeV) = √4694 MeV²/c² = 68.5 MeV/c = 68.5/(197.3) fm⁻¹ × ℏ ≈ 0.347 ℏ/fm. Nuclear radius: R = 1.2 × 40^(1/3) = 1.2 × 3.42 = 4.10 fm. p_n R/ℏ = 0.347 × 4.10 = 1.42. sin(θ_max) = ℓ/1.42: ℓ=0: sin = 0 → θ = 0°; ℓ=1: sin = 0.70 → θ = 44°; ℓ=2: sin = 1.41 → no real solution (>90°, peak near 90°); ℓ=3: θ = sin⁻¹(3/1.42) — this ratio exceeds 1, suggesting the simplified PWBA fails here; more accurately for ℓ=3, the peak is typically ~10–15° from DWBA. The observed peak at ~12° is consistent with ℓ = 3 from full DWBA calculations, matching the f₇/₂ assignment of the ⁴¹Ca ground state."
