                answer: "For H₂O: ξ_eff ≈ 0.92 (mixture of H and O); macroscopic Σ_s ≈ 1.5 cm⁻¹; Σ_a ≈ 0.022 cm⁻¹ (dominated by H absorption). Moderating ratio ≈ 0.92 × 1.5/0.022 ≈ 62. For graphite (density 1.6 g/cm³): ξ = 0.158; Σ_s ≈ 0.385 cm⁻¹; Σ_a ≈ 0.00032 cm⁻¹. Moderating ratio ≈ 0.158 × 0.385/0.00032 ≈ 190. The graphite moderating ratio is ~3× higher than water's. The critical difference is the absorption: water's hydrogen absorbs neutrons with σ_a = 0.33 b — each absorption represents a neutron lost from the chain reaction. Natural uranium is only 0.72% U-235; with water absorbing many neutrons, there are insufficient neutrons left to maintain criticality with natural uranium. Graphite absorbs ~100× fewer neutrons per moderator atom, leaving enough neutrons for criticality even with natural uranium. This is why CANDU (heavy water) and Magnox (graphite) reactors can use natural uranium, while light water reactors must use enriched uranium (3–5% U-235)."
