                answer: "Number of collisions: H₂O ≈ 18 (dominated by H, ξ ≈ 1.0); D₂O ≈ 25 (dominated by D, ξ ≈ 0.725). For each collision: probability of absorption (instead of scattering) = σ_a/(σ_a + σ_s). For H: σ_a = 0.33 b, σ_s = 20 b → P_abs = 0.33/20.33 = 0.016 per collision. For D: σ_a = 0.00053 b, σ_s = 3.4 b → P_abs = 0.00053/3.40 = 0.000156 per collision. Absorptions per thermalisation: H: 0.016 × 18 = 0.29 absorptions/thermalisation; D: 0.000156 × 25 = 0.0039 absorptions/thermalisation. D₂O produces ~75× fewer neutron absorptions per thermalisation despite needing more collisions. In a reactor, neutron economy is critical — each absorbed moderator neutron is one fewer available to sustain fission. D₂O's extraordinarily low absorption makes it worth the cost (~$300/kg versus ~$0.001/kg for H₂O) for reactors designed to use natural uranium fuel."
