        introduction: "In 1929, Ernest Orlando Lawrence at the University of California, Berkeley, conceived the cyclotron — a resonant particle accelerator — while reading a paper by Rolf Wideröe on linear accelerators. Lawrence recognised that a charged particle in a magnetic field travels in a circle, and that if the field is chosen correctly, the orbital period is independent of the particle's speed — a crucial insight that would allow particles to be accelerated to high energy by repeatedly applying the same alternating voltage.",

        aim: "Lawrence's aim was to design an accelerator that could produce high-energy particles without requiring dangerously high voltages — by instead applying a modest voltage many times in synchrony with the particle's circular orbit. The central technical problem was to verify that the cyclotron resonance condition (constant orbital period regardless of speed) held for practical proton energies.",

        subject: "The subject of Lawrence's experiments was the circular motion of protons (and later deuterons and alpha particles) in a uniform magnetic field, accelerated by an alternating electric field applied across a D-shaped gap. The 27-inch and 37-inch cyclotrons at Berkeley became the world's first powerful particle accelerators.",

        subjectDefinition: "The cyclotron frequency (also called the cyclotron resonance frequency) is the frequency at which a charged particle completes one orbit in a uniform magnetic field: f_c = qB/(2πm). For a particle of charge q, mass m, in a field B, this frequency is independent of the particle's speed (in the non-relativistic limit) — the key insight that makes the cyclotron work. As the particle accelerates and its radius increases, each orbit takes the same time, so the same alternating voltage accelerates the particle on every half-turn.",

        results: "Lawrence and his student M. Stanley Livingston demonstrated cyclotron resonance acceleration in 1930 with a hand-sized prototype, producing 80 keV protons. By 1932 they had produced 1.22 MeV protons — sufficient to split the lithium atom. The cyclotron frequency formula f_c = qB/(2πm) was verified precisely: the resonance frequency for protons at B = 1 T is approximately 15.2 MHz. Lawrence received the 1939 Nobel Prize in Physics for the invention of the cyclotron.",

