                answer: "A charged particle moving with velocity v perpendicular to a uniform magnetic field B experiences a Lorentz force F = qvB (centripetal). For circular motion: F = mv²/r → qvB = mv²/r → r = mv/(qB). The circumference of the orbit is 2πr = 2πmv/(qB). The period T = circumference/speed = 2πmv/(qBv) = 2πm/(qB). Crucially, v cancels — the period is independent of speed. The cyclotron frequency: f_c = 1/T = qB/(2πm). Physical reason: as the particle speeds up, it moves in a larger circle (r ∝ v), but the longer circumference is exactly compensated by the higher speed. The time per orbit remains constant, perfectly synchronised with the fixed RF dee voltage — this is the resonance condition that makes the cyclotron work. It is analogous to a pendulum whose period is independent of amplitude (for small oscillations), but here it's exact rather than approximate in the non-relativistic limit."
