                answer: "γ = 1 + KE/(m₀c²) = 1 + 6.5×10¹² eV / 938.3×10⁶ eV = 1 + 6,927 ≈ 6,928. v/c = √(1 − 1/γ²) = √(1 − 1/6928²) = √(1 − 2.08×10⁻⁸) ≈ 1 − 1.04×10⁻⁸. The protons travel at 0.9999999896c — indistinguishable from c for most purposes. Revolution frequency: f = v/(2πR) = (2.998×10⁸ × 0.9999999896)/(2π × 2804) = 2.998×10⁸/17,615 ≈ 11,245 Hz ≈ 11.245 kHz. Compare to the non-relativistic cyclotron frequency of 22.8 MHz for protons at B≈1T — at LHC energies, the revolution frequency is 2,000× lower because the orbit is vastly larger. The LHC must continuously adjust both B (up to 8.3 T from superconducting magnets) and RF frequency to maintain resonance as protons accelerate — this is the synchrotron principle."
