                answer: "Two problems arise when scaling a classical cyclotron to higher energies: (1) Relativistic mass increase: as proton KE increases above ~9 MeV, γ becomes significant (γ = 1 + 9/938 ≈ 1.010 at 9 MeV). The effective mass increases to γm₀, making the cyclotron period T = 2πγm₀/(qB) longer — the particle falls out of resonance with the fixed dee frequency. In the classical cyclotron this is corrected by the synchrocyclotron (pulsed beam, decreasing RF frequency), but this reduces beam current by ~1000×. (2) Vertical defocusing: in a uniform field, a particle displaced vertically experiences no restoring force; at large radii the field must decrease with radius to maintain isochronism — but a decreasing field defocuses the beam vertically, causing beam loss. The AVF (isochronous cyclotron) solution: the magnetic field varies azimuthally with 'hills' (high B) and 'valleys' (low B), alternating around the magnet poles. The time-averaged field can be made to increase with radius (compensating relativistic mass increase — the 'isochronous condition') while the alternating gradient of the flutter field provides strong vertical focusing. This gives continuous (non-pulsed) high-current beams at fixed RF frequency, as used in all modern medical cyclotrons."
