answer: "Non-relativistic approximation: KE_threshold = |Q|×(m_p + m_p)/m_p = 1876.6 × 2 = 3753 MeV = 3.75 GeV. Relativistic formula: s_threshold = (4m_p c²)² = (4 × 938.3)² = (3753.2)² = 14,087,000 MeV². Using s = (2m_p c² + T)² − T² + 2m_p c² × T... more cleanly: s = 2m_p c²(m_p c² + T) + (m_p c²)² + (m_p c²)² = 2m_p²c⁴ + 2m_p c² T + 2m_p²c⁴ — wait, using s = (m_p c² + KE + m_p c²)² − (p_p c)² = 4m_p²c⁴ + 4m_p c² × KE (approximate). Set 4m_p²c⁴ + 4m_p c²×KE_lab = 16m_p²c⁴. 4m_p c²×KE_lab = 12m_p²c⁴. KE_lab = 3m_p c² = 3 × 938.3 = 2814.9 MeV ≈ 2.815 GeV... exact: KE_threshold = (Σm_out² − Σm_in²)c⁴/(2m_target c²) = ((4m_p)² − (2m_p)²)c⁴/(2m_p c²) = (16−4)m_p²c⁴/(2m_p c²) = 6m_p c² = 6 × 938.3 = 5629.8 MeV ≈ 5.63 GeV. The Bevatron was designed for 6.2 GeV (above threshold with margin). The non-relativistic approximation (3.75 GeV) is badly wrong — the reaction is not non-relativistic since |Q| ~ 2m_p c², far from the NR limit. The relativistic result (5.63 GeV) correctly matches the Bevatron design energy."
