answer: "LHC collider: √s = 2 × 7 TeV = 14 TeV → s = 196 TeV² = 196×10²⁴ MeV². Fixed target equivalent: s = 2m_p c²(m_p c² + T) ≈ 2m_p c² × T (since T >> m_p c²). T_fixed = s/(2m_p c²) = 196×10²⁴ / (2 × 938.3) MeV = 196×10²⁴/1876.6 MeV = 1.044×10²³ MeV = 1.044×10¹⁷ eV ≈ 1.04×10⁸ GeV = 104 PeV. Compare to LHC per-beam energy of 7 TeV = 7×10³ GeV. Ratio: 1.04×10⁸ / 7×10³ = 14,857. The fixed-target beam would need to be ~15,000× more energetic than the LHC per-beam energy (or ~7,500× the centre-of-mass energy) to achieve the same √s. This dramatically illustrates why particle physics beyond ~100 GeV is done exclusively with colliders — fixed-target machines become hopelessly energy-inefficient as the square root of the available energy scales with beam energy, while collider √s scales linearly with beam energy."
