                answer: "Liquid drop model alone predicts approximately symmetric fission — the symmetric split minimises Coulomb repulsion between fragments of equal charge. The observed asymmetry requires the nuclear shell model. The key insight is that the heavy fragment strongly prefers to contain N=82 neutrons (the magic closed shell of Ba-138 or nearby nuclides). The N=82 shell provides ~2 MeV extra binding per nucleon to the heavy fragment compared to non-magic alternatives. For the symmetric split, both fragments would have N≈62 — non-magic, less bound. For the asymmetric split (heavy fragment N≈82, light fragment N≈52), the total binding energy is ~4–8 MeV higher than the symmetric case. This energy difference, while small compared to the 200 MeV total release, is sufficient to make asymmetric fission overwhelmingly probable at thermal neutron energies where the system explores available phase space. The transition state (saddle point) energy is lower for asymmetric deformation because the N=82 shell is pre-formed in the elongated nucleus before scission."
