                question: "A CANDU reactor uses heavy water (D₂O) as both moderator and coolant. Explain why this choice allows the use of natural uranium (0.7% U-235) while a comparable light water reactor (LWR) requires 3–5% enriched uranium.",
                hint: "Compare the moderating ratios of D₂O and H₂O and the implications for neutron economy.",
                answer: "Moderating ratio (MR) = ξΣ_s/Σ_a: H₂O MR ≈ 62; D₂O MR ≈ 5,000. The moderating ratio quantifies the number of neutrons slowed per neutron absorbed in the moderator. In an LWR, for every ~62 neutrons that are successfully moderated (slowed to thermal energy), the moderator absorbs ~1 — representing a significant neutron loss. This parasitic absorption reduces the thermal utilisation factor f and decreases k_∞. With natural uranium (only 0.7% U-235), k_∞ ≈ 1.05 for D₂O lattice but k_∞ ≈ 0.85 for H₂O lattice — subcritical in light water regardless of size (leakage drives it further below 1). The CANDU solution: D₂O's 600× better moderating ratio captures essentially all neutrons in the moderator without absorbing them, giving k_∞ ≈ 1.12 — sufficient for criticality with natural uranium even accounting for leakage and fission product absorption. The LWR must enrich uranium to 3–5% U-235 to compensate for H₂O's parasitic absorption and achieve k_∞ sufficiently above 1 for criticality with practical reactor sizes."
