                answer: "B-10 absorption: ¹⁰B(n,α)⁷Li — the B-10 nucleus is destroyed in the reaction; it is transmuted to lithium and helium and removed from the neutron-absorbing inventory. A single B-10 atom can only absorb one neutron before being consumed. After ~3 years of PWR operation, boron-carbide rods lose ~50% of their control worth as B-10 is depleted. Hafnium absorption: Hf has five stable isotopes (⁵Hf¹⁷⁴, ¹⁷⁶, ¹⁷⁷, ¹⁷⁸, ¹⁷⁹, ¹⁸⁰). When ¹⁷⁶Hf absorbs a neutron it becomes ¹⁷⁷Hf (also absorbs well), which becomes ¹⁷⁸Hf (absorbs), ¹⁷⁹Hf (absorbs), ¹⁸⁰Hf (absorbs), ¹⁸¹Hf (β⁻ decays to Ta-181). Each hafnium atom can absorb 4–5 neutrons sequentially before exhaustion, and the intermediate isotopes all have significant cross-sections. The result is that hafnium control rods maintain their control worth over a much longer fuel cycle (~10 years) compared to B-4C. This advantage outweighs hafnium's lower initial cross-section in applications where long rod lifetime is important. Hafnium is also a metal (unlike B-4C ceramic), giving better mechanical ductility and resistance to cracking."
