                answer: "In an SFR, neutrons are maintained at fast (MeV) energies by absence of any moderating material. Nuclear physics reasons: (1) Fast neutrons have higher η (neutrons per fission) in Pu-239: η_fast(Pu-239) ≈ 2.9–3.1 vs η_thermal ≈ 2.15 — producing ~1 extra neutron per fission. (2) U-238 has significant fast fission cross-section (σ_f ≈ 0.6 b at 1 MeV vs negligible at thermal energies) — natural and depleted uranium contributes to fission power. (3) Fast neutrons can efficiently fission the minor actinides (Am, Cm, Np) that accumulate in thermal reactors as waste — transmuting them to fission products with much shorter half-lives. Fuel implications: SFRs typically require 15–20% Pu or high-enriched U fuel because U-235 fast fission cross-section is lower than thermal. However, the breeding ratio can exceed 1.0 — the reactor produces more fissile material (Pu-239 from U-238 capture) than it consumes. A breeding ratio of 1.2 means the reactor produces 20% more fuel than it uses, eventually enabling use of the vast U-238 resource (99.3% of natural uranium) as fuel rather than just U-235 (0.7%). Waste management: actinide transmutation in SFRs can reduce the radiotoxic lifetime of spent fuel from ~10⁶ years to ~1,000 years — one of the primary motivations for Generation IV SFR development."
