                answer: "Reaction heat per kg of Zr: ΔH/kg = 620,000 / 0.0912 = 6.8×10⁶ J/kg = 6.8 MJ/kg. A typical PWR has ~25,000 kg of zircaloy cladding. If all reacted: total heat = 6.8×10⁶ × 25,000 = 1.7×10¹¹ J = 170 GJ. This is released in addition to fission product decay heat. Decay heat comparison: at 24 hours after shutdown of a 3 GW reactor ≈ 20 MW = 20×10⁶ J/s. The Zr-water reaction heat of 170 GJ would be equivalent to 170×10⁹/20×10⁶ ≈ 8,500 seconds ≈ 2.4 hours of additional heat at the 24-hour decay heat rate — significant aggravation. Fukushima hydrogen concern: at Fukushima units 1, 2, 3, steam contacted exposed zircaloy at ~1,200°C (above the 850°C onset temperature for rapid Zr oxidation). Each reactor produced several hundred kg of H₂. The hydrogen accumulated in the reactor building above the containment. H₂ at 4–75% concentration in air is explosive. Explosions at units 1, 2, and 3 blew off the building roofs, damaging structures and releasing fission products. The hydrogen detonations were not nuclear explosions — containment was not breached in units 1 and 3 immediately — but the structural damage worsened the accident progression and contributed to fission product release."
