                hint: "TRISO = kernel + buffer + IPyC + SiC + OPyC layers. Consider the temperature margin to the 1,600°C failure threshold.",
                answer: "TRISO structure (from inside out): (1) Uranium oxycarbide kernel (~500 μm diameter): contains fissile U-235 (enriched 8–20%); generates fission products. (2) Porous pyrolytic carbon buffer (~100 μm): attenuates fission recoils and provides void space for fission gases and kernel swelling without stressing outer layers. (3) Inner pyrolytic carbon (IPyC, ~40 μm): pressure vessel pre-compression; prevents Cl-based chemical attack of SiC layer during deposition; provides additional fission gas containment. (4) Silicon carbide (SiC, ~35 μm): the primary pressure vessel and main fission product diffusion barrier; SiC has very low diffusivity for most fission products (Cs, Sr, Ag) at temperatures below 1,600°C; thermally stable to 2,700°C. (5) Outer pyrolytic carbon (OPyC, ~40 μm): protects SiC from mechanical damage during fuel element fabrication and provides additional fission product containment. The 1,600°C failure threshold arises from SiC decomposition above this temperature, allowing fission product release. In normal HTGR operation (maximum fuel temperature ~1,200–1,250°C), there is a 350–400°C temperature margin below SiC failure. Even during a loss-of-coolant accident in a modular HTGR (e.g. PBMR), the maximum fuel temperature is limited to ~1,600°C by the low power density and high heat capacity of the graphite moderator — the reactor can never exceed SiC failure temperature passively, without operator action or active cooling. This gives the HTGR an inherent safety characteristic: fission product containment is guaranteed by ceramic materials rather than by active cooling systems."
