        aim: "The aim of the Los Alamos critical mass calculations was to determine: the minimum mass of U-235 or Pu-239 for which k_prompt > 1 (prompt supercritical); how this mass depends on the shape (sphere is minimum surface-to-volume ratio); how a neutron reflector (tamper) surrounding the fissile core reduces the critical mass; and how compressing the material to above-normal density reduces critical mass.",

        subject: "The subjects of these analyses were sub-critical assemblies of highly enriched uranium (HEU, >90% U-235) and Pu-239 metal, approaching criticality in measured steps at the Omega Site experiments — the 'tickling the dragon's tail' experiments that killed Louis Slotin in 1946 when the assembly accidentally achieved criticality.",

        subjectDefinition: "Critical mass (m_c) is the minimum mass of fissile material in which a self-sustaining prompt neutron chain reaction can occur. For a bare sphere: m_c ∝ (1/σ_fission)³ × (1/ρ)² × (M/Nₐ)³. The critical radius r_c = (1/σ_f × n)^{1/2} × (Buckling factor). Three factors reduce critical mass: (1) Geometry — sphere minimises surface-to-volume ratio and thus neutron leakage; (2) Neutron reflector (tamper) — surrounds the core, reflects escaping neutrons back inward; (3) Compression — increasing density ρ above normal reduces r_c as r_c ∝ 1/ρ, and m_c ∝ 1/ρ².",

        results: "Los Alamos calculations gave the bare sphere critical mass for U-235 (HEU): ~52 kg. With a natural uranium reflector (20 cm thick): ~15 kg. Pu-239 bare sphere: ~10 kg. Pu-239 with beryllium reflector: ~4 kg. Compressing Pu-239 to 2.5× normal density (by implosion lens): critical mass falls to ~0.64 kg — the basis for the Fat Man implosion bomb. The Trinity test (16 July 1945) used an implosion device with 6.2 kg of Pu-239 compressed to supercritical density by 32 explosive lenses.",

        modernConnection: "Critical mass calculations are the foundation of nuclear weapons physics but also of nuclear criticality safety in civilian nuclear facilities (fuel fabrication, reprocessing, waste storage). The investigation below trains students to apply the one-group diffusion theory formula for critical mass, calculate how reflectors and density changes modify the critical mass, and understand why geometry, enrichment, and moderation all affect criticality.",

