                answer: "In the CM frame (D+T nearly at rest): p_initial = 0. After reaction: p_α + p_n = 0 → p_α = −p_n → |p_α|² = |p_n|² = p². Kinetic energies: KE_α = p²/(2m_α); KE_n = p²/(2m_n). Ratio: KE_α/KE_n = m_n/m_α = 1.009/4.003 = 0.2520. Total: KE_α + KE_n = Q = 17.589 MeV. Solving: KE_n = Q/(1 + m_n/m_α) = 17.589/(1 + 0.2520) = 17.589/1.252 = 14.047 MeV ✓. KE_α = Q − KE_n = 17.589 − 14.047 = 3.542 MeV ✓. Accepted values: 14.07 MeV (neutron), 3.52 MeV (alpha) — agreement within rounding. Physical meaning: equal momenta → lighter particle (neutron, m=1) has more kinetic energy (KE = p²/2m — smaller m means larger KE for same p). The neutron carries 80% of the energy despite being only 20% of the total product mass — a counterintuitive result that is fundamental to all fusion reactor blanket design."
