        subjectDefinition: "The Lawson criterion is a minimum condition on the 'fusion triple product' n × τ_E × T for net energy production from a thermonuclear plasma. For D-T fusion, ignition (self-sustaining burning without external heating) requires: n × τ_E × T ≥ 3×10²¹ m⁻³ s keV. The triple product combines three independent plasma parameters — density (n), energy confinement time (τ_E), and ion temperature (T) — that must all be achieved simultaneously. Progress in fusion research is measured by how close experiments approach the Lawson triple product.",

        results: "Lawson calculated that for D-T at T ≈ 10–15 keV (optimum temperature), nτ_E ≥ 2×10²⁰ m⁻³ s is required for ignition. The original Lawson parameter nτ was later extended to the triple product nτT, which is temperature-independent and more useful for comparing experiments at different temperatures. Since 1970, fusion triple product has increased by a factor of ~10,000 (from 10¹⁷ to 10²¹ m⁻³ s keV), with JET achieving 1.53×10²¹ m⁻³ s keV in 1997 and NIF achieving ignition with a different metric in 2022.",

        modernConnection: "The Lawson triple product is the standard metric for measuring progress in fusion research — it is plotted on 'Lawson diagrams' that compare all fusion experiments from the 1960s to ITER projections. The investigation below trains students to derive the Lawson criterion, plot the triple product on a log-scale progress chart, compare experiments, and understand what physical improvements have driven the 10,000-fold increase since 1970.",

