                answer: "Per unit volume: Alpha heating: P_alpha/V = (1/4)n² × <σv> × 0.2 × Q_DT [W/m³]. (n/2 = density of each species; (n/2)² × <σv> is the reaction rate density; 0.2×Q is the alpha energy per reaction). Conduction loss: P_cond/V = (3/2)n × k_B × T / τ_E [W/m³] (total kinetic energy per unit volume = (3/2)nkT for single temperature plasma; each ion has average energy 3kT/2). Set P_alpha = P_cond: (1/4)n² × <σv> × 0.2 × Q = (3/2)n × k_B × T / τ_E. Solving for nτ_E: nτ_E = (3/2 × k_B × T) / (0.2 × Q × <σv>/4) = (3/2 × k_B × T × 4) / (0.2 × Q × <σv>) = 6 k_B T / (0.2 × Q × <σv>). At T = 15 keV, k_B T = 15×10³ × 1.602×10⁻¹⁹ = 2.4×10⁻¹⁵ J; <σv> ≈ 2.33×10⁻²² m³/s; Q = 17.59×10⁶ × 1.602×10⁻¹⁹ = 2.82×10⁻¹² J. nτ_E = 6 × 2.4×10⁻¹⁵ / (0.2 × 2.82×10⁻¹² × 2.33×10⁻²²) = 1.44×10⁻¹⁴ / (1.315×10⁻³⁴) = 1.1×10²⁰ m⁻³ s. This is the simplified Lawson nτ criterion; the full triple product nτT = 1.1×10²⁰ × 15 keV = 1.65×10²¹ m⁻³ s keV (close to the accepted 3×10²¹ with more careful treatment)."
