                hint: "nτ_E ∝ T / <σv>. Since <σv> rises faster than T at first, the ratio T/<σv> decreases up to T_opt then increases again.",
                answer: "From nτ_E ∝ T/<σv>(T): at T = 1 keV: T/<σv> ≈ 1/(10⁻²⁶) = 10²⁶ (very hard to confine — <σv> is tiny at low T). At T = 10 keV: <σv> ≈ 10⁻²³ m³/s; T/<σv> ≈ 10/(10⁻²³) = 10²⁴ (improving rapidly). At T = 25 keV: <σv> ≈ 3×10⁻²² m³/s (near peak); T/<σv> ≈ 25/(3×10⁻²²) = 8.3×10²² (near minimum). At T = 64 keV (σv peak): <σv> ≈ 10⁻²¹ m³/s; T/<σv> = 64/10⁻²¹ = 6.4×10²² (slightly above minimum). At T = 100 keV: <σv> decreasing back to ~5×10⁻²² m³/s; T/<σv> = 2×10²³ (increasing — getting harder). The optimum temperature is approximately T_opt ≈ 25–30 keV for D-T, where the ratio T/<σv> is minimised. In practice, tokamaks operate at T ≈ 10–20 keV because: (a) the confinement time improves at lower T due to reduced particle transport; (b) plasma heating to 25–30 keV requires more external energy; (c) at 10–15 keV, the product nτT criterion is slightly less stringent when the bremsstrahlung term is included. Engineering constraints typically set the operating temperature at 15–20 keV for near-term devices."
