        subjectDefinition: "Carbon intensity (gCO₂eq/kWh) measures the greenhouse gas emissions per unit of electricity generated over the full lifecycle of a power plant. Levelised cost of electricity (LCOE, $/MWh) is the net present cost of building and operating a plant over its lifetime divided by the total electricity generated — the minimum average price the plant must receive to cover all costs. These two metrics together determine the climate and economic performance of different electricity sources.",

        results: "IPCC AR6 (2022) lifecycle carbon intensities (median values): Coal: 820 gCO₂/kWh; Gas CCGT: 490; Nuclear: 12; Wind onshore: 7; Wind offshore: 9; Solar PV: 27; Hydropower: 24. Nuclear has among the lowest lifecycle carbon intensities of any energy source — comparable to wind and lower than solar. LCOE comparisons (2020–2023) show solar and onshore wind achieving $25–50/MWh in good resources, while new nuclear is $80–120/MWh in Western countries (though $40–60 in South Korea and China). The LCOE comparison therefore favours renewables in most markets, while the carbon intensity comparison favours both equally for climate purposes.",

        modernConnection: "The comparison of nuclear and renewable energy is a central question in 21st century energy policy. This investigation trains students to calculate carbon intensity and LCOE from first principles using physical parameters, apply the results to climate scenarios, and analyse the trade-offs between nuclear and renewables for electricity decarbonisation.",

        contribution: "First comprehensive IPCC comparison of lifecycle emissions from all electricity sources; provided quantitative basis for technology-neutral climate mitigation policies",
