                question: "Nuclear power plants have lifecycle CO₂ of only 12 gCO₂/kWh despite the uranium mining, enrichment (energy-intensive), and construction. Identify the three largest contributors to nuclear's lifecycle emissions and explain why operation itself contributes nearly zero direct CO₂.",
                hint: "Consider which stages involve burning fossil fuels vs operating on uranium fission.",
                answer: "Three largest lifecycle contributors to nuclear CO₂: (1) Uranium enrichment (~30–40% of lifecycle total): uranium enrichment (isotope separation to 3–5% U-235) historically used gaseous diffusion — enormously electricity-intensive (~100 kWh per kg SWU). Modern centrifuge enrichment uses ~50× less electricity (2.5 kWh/SWU). If enrichment electricity comes from coal, this adds ~5–8 gCO₂/kWh. With low-carbon electricity for enrichment, this drops to <1 gCO₂/kWh. (2) Construction (~25–35%): concrete, steel, and other construction materials require energy (cement production emits ~0.9 kg CO₂/kg). A large nuclear plant uses 40,000–50,000 tonnes of steel and 190,000 m³ of concrete. Manufacturing this releases CO₂. (3) Decommissioning and waste management (~10–20%): cutting, handling, and transporting radioactive material uses energy; deep geological repository construction requires significant concrete and steel. Operation (nuclear chain reaction): the fission reaction itself produces no CO₂ whatsoever. The thermal cycle (steam turbines, cooling towers) uses water and electricity but no combustion. Unlike a gas plant where ~97% of CO₂ comes from burning fuel in operation, nuclear's operational phase is essentially zero-carbon. This is why all lifecycle analyses agree that nuclear electricity is inherently low-carbon once the plant is built — the ongoing operation is carbon-free."
