                hint: "W production threshold: √s ≥ m_W c². Van der Meer developed stochastic cooling to concentrate the antiproton beam.",
                answer: "Single W production threshold from quark-antiquark annihilation: q + q̄ → W±. The CM energy of the parton-level collision must exceed m_W c² = 80.4 GeV. However, quarks inside protons carry only a fraction x of the proton momentum (Bjorken x ~ 0.1–0.3). For quark-antiquark CM energy √ŝ ≥ 80.4 GeV from pp̄ at √s = 540 GeV: ŝ = x₁ × x₂ × s = x₁ × x₂ × 540². For typical x₁ = x₂ = 0.15: √ŝ = 0.15 × 540 = 81 GeV ✓ — sufficient. The CERN SPS was upgraded to √s = 540 GeV (later 630 GeV) — sufficient to produce W and Z bosons at acceptable rate. Key innovations by Rubbia and van der Meer: (1) Stochastic cooling: producing antiprotons in large quantities required a 'beam cooler' to reduce the momentum spread of antiprotons from a dense pp̄ target. Van der Meer's stochastic cooling used sensors to detect beam 'kicks' and kickers to compensate them across the ring, reducing beam emittance by factor ~10⁶ and enabling a dense, collimable pp̄ beam. (2) Antiproton accumulator: antiprotons were produced, cooled, and stored in a dedicated antiproton accumulator ring before injection into the SPS. Without stochastic cooling, the luminosity would have been 10⁶× too low to observe W events in a practical time. Rubbia and van der Meer shared the 1984 Nobel Prize in Physics."
