                answer: "Stop squark pair production threshold: √ŝ ≥ 2 × 1000 GeV = 2000 GeV = 2 TeV (at quark-antiquark level). LHC CM energy: √s = 13 TeV (Run 2) or 14 TeV (design). Parton-level CM energy with x₁ = x₂ = 0.15: √ŝ = x₁ × x₂ × s at quark level. More precisely: √ŝ = √(x₁ × x₂) × √s = 0.15 × 13,000 = 1,950 GeV for typical quarks — marginally below threshold for stop pair production at m_stop = 1 TeV. However, some parton-parton collisions involve x values of 0.2–0.3: for x₁ = x₂ = 0.2: √ŝ = 0.2 × 13,000 = 2,600 GeV = 2.6 TeV > 2 TeV threshold ✓. At 14 TeV: √ŝ(0.15) = 2,100 GeV > 2,000 ✓. The LHC at 13–14 TeV can in principle produce stop squarks up to ~1 TeV mass, but with low production cross-section (decreasing steeply with mass). ATLAS and CMS have searched for stop squarks and set lower limits of ~1.2–1.4 TeV (as of 2023) — no stop discovery. This non-observation is a significant constraint on supersymmetry at low mass scales. For a 2 TeV stop, the required parton-level energy of 4 TeV would need LHC at 100 TeV (proposed FCC-hh facility) with x ~ 0.04. The post-Higgs particle physics question 'what comes after the Standard Model?' may require a 100 TeV proton collider to answer."
