                answer: "Let quark charges be of the form Q = n/3 where n is an integer. Specifically: u,c,t have n=+2; d,s,b have n=−1; their antiparticles have n=−2 and n=+1 respectively. Meson (qq̄): total charge = Q₁ + Q₂ where Q₁ = n₁/3 (quark) and Q₂ = n₂/3 (antiquark, n₂ = −n_quark₂). For any meson: possible n combinations (quark + antiquark): (2) + (−2) = 0; (2) + (+1) = 3 = +1e; (−1) + (−2) = −3 = −1e; (−1) + (+1) = 0. All results: 0, ±1 (in units of e). Always integers. Baryon (qqq): total charge = (n₁ + n₂ + n₃)/3 where each nᵢ ∈ {+2, −1}. Possible sums: 3×(+2) = 6 → +2e; 2×(+2)+1×(−1) = 3 → +1e; 1×(+2)+2×(−1) = 0 → 0; 3×(−1) = −3 → −1e. All results: 0, ±1, ±2 (integers). The key: all quark charges are multiples of 1/3, and hadrons contain exactly 3 quarks (or 2, summing to multiples of 3 in numerator). The denominator 3 always cancels exactly, yielding integer charges. This is not a coincidence — the quark charge assignment was specifically chosen to reproduce integer hadron charges, and is deeply connected to the fact that quarks come in three colours (SU(3) gauge theory requires the number of colours to equal the denominator of quark charges for anomaly cancellation)."
