                answer: "Mass prediction: The baryon decuplet (Δ, Σ*, Ξ*, Ω) shows equal mass spacing with each unit of additional strangeness adding ~150 MeV: Δ (uuu/uud/udd/ddd): mass ≈ 1,232 MeV. Σ* (one strange): 1,232 + 147 = 1,379 MeV. Ξ* (two strange): 1,379 + 147 = 1,526 MeV. Ω⁻ (three strange): 1,526 + 147 = 1,673 MeV. Gell-Mann predicted M(Ω⁻) ≈ 1,680 MeV; measured value = 1,672 MeV. Experimental signature: The Ω⁻ was identified in a bubble chamber photograph at BNL in January 1964. The K⁻ + p → Ω⁻ + K⁺ + K⁰ reaction produced an Ω⁻ that left a short track (strangeness S=−3 prevents rapid strong decay — no lighter baryon with S=−3 or more exists for it to decay to via strong interaction). It decayed weakly: Ω⁻ → Λ⁰ + K⁻ or Ω⁻ → Ξ⁰ + π⁻. The weakness of the decay (long lifetime τ~8×10⁻¹¹ s ≫ typical strong decay time 10⁻²³ s) was itself evidence that it contained three strange quarks. The discovery precisely matched the predicted mass, charge (−1), strangeness (−3), and spin (3/2) — providing definitive confirmation of the Eightfold Way and strong evidence for the quark model."
