                answer: "Naive quark model prediction: Proton (uud, spin 1/2). Simplest spin assignment: two u quarks in a spin-singlet (spins cancel): ↑↓ → Σ_u = 0. Remaining d quark carries the proton spin: Σ_d = 1/2. Total quark spin contribution = 1/2 (100% from d). A more careful calculation using SU(6) spin-flavour symmetry gives: Σ_u = +4/3 (in units of 1/2), Σ_d = −1/3, Σ_s = 0, total = +1 (×1/2 = 1/2 total). All proton spin carried by quarks. The proton spin crisis (1988): the European Muon Collaboration (EMC) at CERN measured the spin structure of the proton using polarised muons scattered off polarised protons — deep inelastic scattering measuring the quark helicity distribution Δq = q↑ − q↓. Result: Σ = Δu + Δd + Δs ≈ 0.12 ± 0.17 — consistent with zero, and certainly far below the naive value of ~1. Subsequent experiments refined this to Σ ≈ 0.25–0.33. What this revealed: (1) Gluon spin: gluons inside the proton can carry angular momentum — the gluon helicity ΔG contributes significantly to total proton spin. Modern measurements suggest ΔG ~ 0.3–0.5 (gluons carry ~30–50% of proton spin). (2) Orbital angular momentum: quarks and gluons can have orbital angular momentum L_q and L_g in addition to spin. The full spin sum rule is: 1/2 = 1/2 × Σ + ΔG + L_q + L_g. (3) Sea quarks: virtual ss̄ pairs in the proton (sea quarks) contribute negative polarisation, reducing the measured quark helicity sum. The proton spin crisis showed that the 'simple' quark model picture is insufficient — the proton is a complex many-body quantum field theory system, not just three quarks."
