                answer: "Protons experience both the attractive nuclear force (from all nearest neighbours) and Coulomb repulsion (from all other protons). As Z increases, Coulomb repulsion accumulates from an increasing number of proton-proton pairs, while each proton's nuclear attraction is limited to its near neighbours (~range 2–3 fm). Neutrons experience only the nuclear attractive force — no Coulomb repulsion (they are uncharged). Adding neutrons therefore increases the total nuclear attractive force without adding to Coulomb repulsion, diluting the proton-proton repulsion. Large nuclei require increasing numbers of neutrons relative to protons (N/Z > 1) to maintain stability — lead-208 has Z = 82 protons and N = 126 neutrons (N/Z ≈ 1.54). However, there is a limit: too many neutrons makes the nucleus unstable against beta decay (neutron → proton), so there is an optimal N/Z ratio for each Z."
