        introduction: "In 1949, the German-American physicist Maria Goeppert Mayer and independently the German physicist J. Hans D. Jensen developed the nuclear shell model at the Argonne National Laboratory and the University of Heidelberg respectively, explaining the systematic pattern of nuclear stability in terms of nucleon shell closures — directly addressing why specific numbers of protons and neutrons (2, 8, 20, 28, 50, 82, 126) confer exceptional stability and why the stability band on the N-Z chart has the shape it does.",

        aim: "The aim of Goeppert Mayer and Jensen's investigation was to explain the pattern of nuclear stability — specifically why certain nuclei (magic number nuclei) are exceptionally stable, why the band of stability curves away from N = Z for heavy nuclei, and why nuclei outside the stability band undergo specific types of radioactive decay to return toward stability.",

        subject: "The subject of the investigation was the entire chart of nuclides — a two-dimensional map of all known nuclei plotted with neutron number N on one axis and proton number Z on the other — with stable nuclei forming a narrow band (the valley of stability) surrounded by unstable nuclei that undergo alpha, beta-minus, beta-plus, or positron emission decay.",

        subjectDefinition: "The neutron-to-proton ratio (N/Z) is a key determinant of nuclear stability. For light nuclei (A < 40), the most stable nuclides have approximately equal numbers of protons and neutrons (N/Z ≈ 1), satisfying the pairing symmetry energy term in the semi-empirical mass formula. For heavier nuclei, the increasing Coulomb repulsion between protons is partly offset by adding extra neutrons (which contribute nuclear binding without Coulomb repulsion), shifting the stability line to N/Z > 1. The band of stability is the region of the N-Z plot where stable nuclei exist; nuclei above the band (too many neutrons, N/Z too high) decay by beta-minus emission (n → p), and nuclei below the band (too many protons, N/Z too low) decay by beta-plus/positron emission or electron capture (p → n), both moving toward the stability band.",

        results: "The nuclear shell model explained the stability band's shape, the magic numbers, and the decay modes of unstable nuclei. The chart of nuclides contains ~3300 known nuclides, of which ~254 are stable — all lying on the stability band. The model predicted that the stability band curves increasingly above N = Z for Z > 20, reaching N/Z ≈ 1.5 for lead (Z = 82) — confirmed by all known stable heavy nuclei. Goeppert Mayer and Jensen received the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1963.",

        modernConnection: "The investigation below uses the chart of nuclides to map the stability band, determine N/Z ratios for representative stable nuclides, identify decay modes for unstable nuclides outside the band, and verify that beta decay moves nuclei toward the stability band.",

        contribution: "Nuclear shell model explaining magic numbers; explanation of stability band shape; prediction of decay modes from N/Z ratio",
        significance: "Unified nuclear stability theory; predicted the decay modes of then-unknown isotopes; underpins modern nuclear medicine isotope selection",
        quote: "The shell model of the nucleus is one of the most successful models in all of physics"
