                answer: "Z increases by 1 (42 → 43) and N decreases by 1 (57 → 56) — A remains 99. This is beta-minus decay: a neutron converts to a proton. ⁹⁹₄₂Mo → ⁹⁹ᵐ₄₃Tc + ⁰₋₁e + v̄_e. The product is technetium-99m (metastable excited state), which then decays by gamma emission (isomeric transition) to ground state ⁹⁹Tc. ⁹⁹ᵐTc is the most widely used medical imaging isotope in nuclear medicine, with a 6-hour half-life that is long enough for imaging but short enough to minimise patient radiation dose."
