            {
                question: "Plot the position of carbon-14 (Z = 6, N = 8) on the N-Z chart relative to the stability band (where ¹²C with Z = 6, N = 6 is stable). Show with an arrow where ¹⁴C moves after beta-minus decay. What is the product nuclide?",
                hint: "Beta-minus decay: Z increases by 1, N decreases by 1, A unchanged.",
                answer: "¹⁴C: Z = 6, N = 8. The stable carbon isotope ¹²C is at Z = 6, N = 6. On the N-Z chart, ¹⁴C is 2 neutron positions above ¹²C — above the stability band (excess neutrons). After beta-minus decay: Z increases by 1 → Z = 7 (nitrogen); N decreases by 1 → N = 7; A unchanged = 14. Product: ¹⁴₇N (nitrogen-14). Decay equation: ¹⁴₆C → ¹⁴₇N + ⁰₋₁e + v̄_e. The arrow on the N-Z chart points diagonally down-right (Z +1, N −1), ending at ¹⁴N which lies on the stability band (Z = 7, N = 7, N/Z = 1.00). ¹⁴C has a half-life of 5730 years — the basis of radiocarbon dating."
            },
            {
                question: "Lead-208 (Z = 82, N = 126) is a doubly magic nucleus. Explain what 'doubly magic' means and why these nuclei have particularly high stability compared to their neighbours.",
                hint: "Apply the nuclear shell model analogy to electrons in atomic orbitals.",
                answer: "In the nuclear shell model (proposed by Goeppert Mayer and Jensen), nucleons fill discrete energy levels (shells) analogous to electron shells in atoms. When a shell is completely full, the nucleus gains extra binding energy — analogous to the extra stability of noble gas electron configurations. 'Magic numbers' of nucleons (2, 8, 20, 28, 50, 82, 126) correspond to completely filled nuclear shells. A 'doubly magic' nucleus has both Z and N equal to magic numbers simultaneously. ²⁰⁸Pb has Z = 82 and N = 126 — both proton and neutron shells are completely filled. This double shell closure gives ²⁰⁸Pb exceptionally high binding energy per nucleon compared to its neighbours (isotopes ²⁰⁶Pb, ²⁰⁷Pb, ²⁰⁹Pb, and bismuth-209), making it the heaviest fully stable nucleus. Other doubly magic nuclei include ⁴He (Z = 2, N = 2), ¹⁶O (Z = 8, N = 8), ⁴⁰Ca (Z = 20, N = 20), and ⁴⁸Ca (Z = 20, N = 28)."
            },
            {
                question: "The proton-rich nucleus ²²Na (Z = 11, N = 11) lies below the stability band. It can decay by either beta-plus emission or electron capture. Write equations for both decay modes and explain under what circumstances each is preferred.",
                hint: "Beta-plus: Z → Z−1 with positron emission. Electron capture: Z → Z−1 by capturing an orbital electron.",
                answer: "Beta-plus emission: ²²₁₁Na → ²²₁₀Ne + ⁰₊₁e + νe. The nucleus emits a positron (antielectron) and a neutrino; Z decreases by 1, N increases by 1. Electron capture: ²²₁₁Na + ⁰₋₁e → ²²₁₀Ne + νe. The nucleus captures an inner orbital electron; Z decreases by 1, N increases by 1. Both produce the same daughter nuclide (²²Ne). The preference depends on the Q-value (energy released): Beta-plus emission requires Q > 2m_e c² = 1.022 MeV to create the positron — the nuclear mass difference must exceed 1.022 MeV. If Q < 1.022 MeV, only electron capture is energetically possible. If Q > 1.022 MeV, both modes can occur with competing probabilities. For ²²Na, Q ≈ 2.84 MeV, so both modes occur, with beta-plus emission dominating (~90.4%) due to higher transition probability when sufficiently energetic. Electron capture is detectable by the X-ray emission that follows inner electron replacement."
            }
