        results: "Goeppert Mayer demonstrated that the nuclear shell model with spin-orbit coupling correctly reproduced all observed magic numbers. She showed that magic number nuclei have: higher binding energies than neighbours; more stable isotopes; larger first excitation energies (harder to perturb); anomalously small neutron capture cross-sections; and high natural abundances. The shell model became the foundation of nuclear structure theory. Goeppert Mayer shared the 1963 Nobel Prize in Physics with Jensen (who independently derived the same results) and Wigner.",

        modernConnection: "The investigation below uses atomic shell filling (which students are more familiar with) as an analogy for nuclear shell filling, comparing patterns of stability, ionisation energies, and melting points in atoms to patterns of binding energy, natural abundance, and number of stable isotopes in nuclei at magic numbers.",

