        subject: "The subject of the unit investigation is the relationship between the SI unit of energy (joule, J) and the electronvolt (eV) — the energy gained by an electron (charge e = 1.60 × 10⁻¹⁹ C) when accelerated through a potential difference of exactly one volt — and the extended units keV, MeV, and GeV used at different scales of nuclear and particle physics.",

        subjectDefinition: "The electronvolt (eV) is defined as the kinetic energy gained by a particle carrying one elementary charge (1e = 1.60 × 10⁻¹⁹ C) when accelerated through a potential difference of one volt: 1 eV = 1.60 × 10⁻¹⁹ J. Multiple units are used at different energy scales: 1 keV = 10³ eV = 1.60 × 10⁻¹⁶ J (X-ray and electron transitions); 1 MeV = 10⁶ eV = 1.60 × 10⁻¹³ J (nuclear processes, alpha/beta/gamma energies); 1 GeV = 10⁹ eV = 1.60 × 10⁻¹⁰ J (particle physics, quark masses); 1 TeV = 10¹² eV = 1.60 × 10⁻⁷ J (LHC collision energies). The mass-energy equivalence E = mc² is often expressed with masses in MeV/c² (proton rest mass ≈ 938 MeV/c²).",

