                hint: "Mean = sum/10; σ = √(Σ(N−N̄)²/9); compare σ to √N̄.",
                answer: "Sum = 295; Mean N̄ = 29.5. Deviations squared: (28−29.5)² + (31−29.5)² + ... = 2.25+2.25+20.25+12.25+6.25+0.25+0.25+30.25+12.25+2.25 = 88.5. σ = √(88.5/9) = √9.83 = 3.14. √N̄ = √29.5 = 5.43. The measured σ (3.14) is somewhat less than the Poisson prediction √N̄ (5.43) — this is common with only 10 measurements, where sampling variation affects the estimate of σ. With 50+ measurements, σ and √N̄ should agree within ~10–20%. The result is broadly consistent with Poisson statistics, suggesting random (not systematic) variation."
