                answer: "At sea level, the atmosphere provides approximately 1000 g/cm² of shielding between cosmic rays entering at the top of the atmosphere and ground level. This thick air shield absorbs most primary cosmic rays (high-energy protons and heavy nuclei) and their secondary shower particles. At 10 km altitude, the remaining air column is approximately 250 g/cm² — only about ¼ of the sea-level shielding. More cosmic ray secondary particles (mainly muons, protons, neutrons, and electrons from extensive air showers) reach the aircraft, increasing dose rate by ~50× compared to sea level. Additionally, solar particle events (SPE) during solar flares can increase dose rates further. Airline pilots and cabin crew flying long-haul routes receive approximately 3–6 mSv/year from cosmic radiation — 3× the average public dose from all sources (~1.5 mSv/year in UK), exceeding the occupational dose limit for some workers. This is why pregnancy must be declared by cabin crew and flight hours are regulated."
