        aim: "The aim of Rutherford's investigation was to characterise and distinguish the different types of ionising radiation emitted by radioactive substances, specifically by measuring how each type was absorbed by progressively greater thicknesses of material and by magnetic and electric field deflection experiments.",

        subject: "The subjects of Rutherford's investigation were the radiations emitted by uranium and thorium compounds, studied through their differential absorption in aluminium foil layers, their ionisation of air (measured by electrometer), and their deflection by electric and magnetic fields.",

        subjectDefinition: "Ionising radiation from radioactive decay comprises three main types: Alpha radiation (α): helium-4 nuclei (charge +2e, mass 4 u) emitted with kinetic energies ~4–10 MeV. Range in air: ~3–10 cm; stopped by a sheet of paper or a few cm of air; causes dense ionisation along a short, straight track. Beta radiation (β): high-speed electrons (β⁻) or positrons (β⁺) emitted with a continuous energy spectrum up to a maximum kinetic energy (endpoint energy). Range in air: ~1–3 m; stopped by a few mm to cm of aluminium; causes less dense ionisation over a longer path. Gamma radiation (γ): high-energy electromagnetic photons emitted in nuclear de-excitation. No charge or mass; penetrates deeply; exponentially attenuated (not completely stopped) by dense materials; requires centimetres of lead or metres of concrete for significant attenuation. The 'half-thickness' of lead for MeV gamma rays is ~1–2 cm.",

        results: "Rutherford demonstrated that alpha radiation was stopped by a single sheet of aluminium foil but produced intense ionisation of air, while beta radiation penetrated several foil thicknesses but ionised less densely. He used magnetic deflection to show beta rays were negatively charged particles (electrons) and alpha rays were positively charged particles of much greater mass. The charge-to-mass ratio confirmed alpha particles as helium nuclei (later confirmed by Geiger and Marsden who collected the helium gas). Gamma rays were identified as undeflected by magnetic fields, confirming electromagnetic (not particle) nature.",

        modernConnection: "The investigation below directly replicates Rutherford's differential absorption method using sealed radioactive check sources, a Geiger-Müller tube, and progressively greater thicknesses of paper, aluminium, and lead to identify and characterise alpha, beta, and gamma radiation.",

        contribution: "Discovered and named alpha and beta radiation; demonstrated their different penetrating powers; used field deflection to determine charge and mass; founded radiation physics",
