                answer: "The inverse square law C ∝ 1/r² strictly applies to a perfect isotropic point source — a source with negligible physical size emitting radiation uniformly in all directions. At distances r much greater than the source dimensions, a real source approximates a point source well. However, at distances comparable to or smaller than the source size (e.g. a source pellet of ~5 mm diameter at r = 5 mm), the source cannot be treated as a point — different parts of the source are at different distances from the detector. The actual count rate falls less steeply than 1/r² at short distances because the detector 'sees' the source as an extended object. Only at r >> source diameter does the 1/r² law become accurately applicable. For typical sealed check sources (~5 mm diameter), the inverse square law is reliable for r > ~5 cm."
