                answer: "Absorbed dose (gray, Gy): measures physical energy deposited per unit mass of tissue (1 Gy = 1 J/kg). It is purely a physical quantity — it makes no assumption about which type of radiation deposited the energy or which organ received it. The same absorbed dose produces very different biological effects depending on radiation type and organ. For example, 1 Gy of alpha particle irradiation to the lung causes ~20× more cancer risk than 1 Gy of gamma irradiation to the same tissue. Absorbed dose is needed for predicting tissue reactions (deterministic effects), heat generation, and material damage. Effective dose (sievert, Sv): accounts for both radiation type (via w_R) and organ sensitivity (via w_T) to provide a single number proportional to overall stochastic cancer risk to the whole body. It allows meaningful comparison between: whole-body gamma irradiation, partial-body alpha irradiation, and neutron exposure to specific organs. Effective dose is used for radiation protection — setting dose limits, comparing exposures, and estimating cancer risk. Both units are necessary: gray for physical and deterministic dose descriptions; sievert for radiation protection, risk communication, and compliance with dose limits."
