                answer: "Conventional decay counting: ¹⁴C atoms are detected by waiting for them to decay (emitting a beta particle) and counting the decay events with a Geiger counter or liquid scintillation counter. For a 10,000-year-old sample, only ~0.32 of ¹⁴C atoms remain per original atom; the ¹⁴C concentration is ~4 × 10⁻¹³ (ratio to ¹²C). In 10 g of carbon, there are ~5 × 10²³ × 10/12 = ~2.5 × 10¹¹ ¹⁴C atoms. Only about 25 of these decay per minute (0.226 × fraction surviving × 10 g / modern ratio) — requiring long counting times for statistical precision. AMS: accelerates carbon ions to MeV energies in a particle accelerator (tandem Van de Graaff). At these energies, ¹⁴C is separated from ¹²C and ¹³C by their different rigidities (momentum/charge) in magnetic and electric fields — each ¹⁴C atom is counted directly as it passes a detector, rather than waiting for it to decay. AMS counts ~10⁸ atoms per second from just 1 mg of carbon, achieving better precision in minutes than decay counting achieves in hours from 10 g — and allowing dating of very small samples (individual seeds, single hairs, art pigments)."
