        results: "The ionisation smoke detector proved highly effective at detecting fast-flaming fires (which produce large amounts of CO₂, combustion gases, and fine smoke particles) — giving earlier warning than photoelectric detectors for this fire type. ²⁴¹Am's 432-year half-life ensures negligible activity decrease over the 10-year design lifetime of the detector. The alpha particles (range ~5 cm in air) are completely stopped within the detector housing — the external dose rate from a domestic smoke detector is immeasurably small. Ionisation smoke detectors are now installed in approximately 90% of domestic properties in the UK and USA.",

        modernConnection: "The investigation below does not work with the actual radioactive source but analyses the physics of the ionisation chamber mechanism — calculating ion current, ion mobility, the effect of smoke on current, and the dose implications of ²⁴¹Am — using a model ionisation chamber and principles from electrostatics.",

