                answer: "Ion pairs per alpha = 5.49 × 10⁶ eV / 33.7 eV = 163,000 ion pairs per alpha. Ion pairs per second = 3.7 × 10⁴ s⁻¹ × 163,000 = 6.03 × 10⁹ pairs/s. Current I = 6.03 × 10⁹ × 1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹ C = 9.6 × 10⁻¹⁰ A = 0.96 pA ≈ 1 pA. The actual current is somewhat less (typically 0.1–0.5 pA) due to ion recombination before collection, but the calculation shows the order of magnitude correctly. This ~1 pA current is easily measured by modern operational amplifier circuits but is far smaller than conventional electrical currents in household wiring (typically milliamperes to amperes)."
