        introduction: "Between 1818 and 1821, the French physicist Augustin-Jean Fresnel developed a rigorous mathematical framework for wave diffraction and interference at the French Academy of Sciences in Paris, introducing the concept of representing wave amplitudes as rotating vectors — now called phasors — to calculate the resultant amplitude when multiple wave components are superposed.",

        aim: "The aim of Fresnel's investigation was to derive a mathematical method for predicting the resultant amplitude and intensity produced when waves from multiple coherent sources of different phases and amplitudes arrive at the same point — moving beyond the qualitative descriptions of Young and Huygens to a precise quantitative theory.",

        subject: "The subjects of Fresnel's theoretical and experimental work were coherent light waves from narrow apertures and slits, whose amplitudes and phases at any observation point he represented as vectors in a two-dimensional plane, with the angle of each vector representing the phase of that wave component.",

        subjectDefinition: "A phasor is a rotating vector whose length represents the amplitude of a wave and whose angle from a reference direction represents the phase of that wave at a given instant. When two waves are superposed, their phasors are added tip-to-tail using vector addition rules; the magnitude of the resultant phasor gives the resultant amplitude A_R, and the resultant intensity is proportional to A_R². For two waves of equal amplitude A and phase difference φ: A_R = 2A·cos(φ/2), and since intensity I ∝ A², the resultant intensity I_R = 4I₀·cos²(φ/2), where I₀ is the intensity of each individual source.",

