                answer: "Temperature is a measure of the mean kinetic energy of gas molecules: (1/2)mv² = (3/2)kT, so v_rms ∝ √T. Sound propagates as a pressure wave by molecular collisions — the speed of sound v is proportional to the speed at which individual molecules travel and transfer momentum: v_sound ∝ v_rms ∝ √T. More precisely, for an ideal gas: v = √(γRT/M), where γ is the adiabatic index (≈1.4 for air), R is the gas constant, T is absolute temperature, and M is molar mass. At 0°C (273 K): v = 331 m/s. At 20°C (293 K): v = 331 × √(293/273) = 331 × 1.036 = 343 m/s. The linear approximation v ≈ 331 + 0.6T (T in °C) is valid for temperatures in the range −30°C to 50°C."
