                answer: "The ear canal is approximately 2.5 cm long and behaves as a tube closed at one end (eardrum) and open at the other. For such a tube, the fundamental resonance frequency is f = v/(4L) = 343/(4 × 0.025) = 343/0.1 = 3430 Hz ≈ 3.4 kHz. At this resonance, the air column in the canal vibrates with maximum amplitude, amplifying pressure at the eardrum by approximately 10–15 dB. This resonance lies in the 1–4 kHz range, explaining why the ear requires the lowest sound intensity to hear frequencies in this region. The resonance also coincides with the frequency range of consonant sounds in human speech (particularly fricatives like 's', 'f', 'th'), suggesting that human hearing evolved to be maximally sensitive to the sounds of our own communication."
