                answer: "A 4 kHz notch on an audiogram is the classic sign of noise-induced hearing loss (NIHL). The most likely cause is prolonged exposure to loud sounds (concerts, heavy machinery, earphones at high volume). Mechanically, the basilar membrane in the cochlea maps frequency spatially — high frequencies are detected near the base, low frequencies near the apex. The 4 kHz region of the basilar membrane is particularly vulnerable because: (1) it is located in the region of maximum mechanical stress during exposure to loud broadband noise; (2) the blood supply is poorest in this region; (3) the outer hair cells that amplify basilar membrane vibration are most fragile at this location. Repeated loud exposures damage and kill these outer hair cells, which cannot regenerate. The 4 kHz notch is often the earliest sign of NIHL and can progress to wider high-frequency loss with continued exposure."
