                answer: "Closed-open tube: at the closed end there must be a displacement node (no air movement); at the open end there must be a displacement antinode (maximum movement). The pattern from node to antinode must fit an odd number of quarter-wavelengths in the tube: L = (2n−1)λ/4 for n = 1, 2, 3... This gives f_n = (2n−1)v/(4L) — only odd multiples of the fundamental: f₁, 3f₁, 5f₁... Closed-closed tube: nodes at both ends — the pattern must fit a whole number of half-wavelengths: L = nλ/2, giving f_n = nv/(2L) — all harmonics present: f₁, 2f₁, 3f₁... An open-open tube also has nodes at both ends (as pressure nodes, i.e. displacement antinodes) and produces all harmonics with the same series as closed-closed but an octave higher in fundamental for the same length."
