                hint: "Consider the role of the end correction and how using two resonance lengths eliminates it.",
                answer: "Using only L₁ with v = 4fL₁ assumes the air column length is exactly λ/4 — but the actual acoustic length is L₁ + e (where e is the end correction, ≈ 0.6r). If e = 0.6 cm and L₁ = 18.8 cm, the true λ/4 = 19.4 cm, not 18.8 cm — a 3.2% error in λ and hence in v. Using both resonances: the end correction e is the same for both L₁ and L₂ (same tube opening). Therefore L₁ + e = λ/4 and L₂ + e = 3λ/4. Subtracting: L₂ − L₁ = λ/2 — the end correction cancels completely. This subtraction method is much more accurate because it eliminates the systematic error introduced by e, which would otherwise give a systematically low value of λ and v."
