                answer: "For an open-open pipe: f_n = nv/(2L). Fundamental (n = 1): f₁ = v/(2L) = 343/(2 × 2.0) = 343/4.0 = 85.75 Hz ≈ 86 Hz. This is approximately the note E2 (82 Hz). Second harmonic (n = 2): f₂ = 2 × 85.75 = 171.5 Hz ≈ 172 Hz. Third harmonic (n = 3): f₃ = 3 × 85.75 = 257.25 Hz ≈ 257 Hz. Fourth harmonic (n = 4): f₄ = 4 × 85.75 = 343 Hz. An open pipe of 2 m length produces a rich series of harmonics; the same pipe length as a stopped (closed-open) pipe would produce f₁ = v/(4L) = 343/8 = 42.9 Hz — an octave lower. This is why stopped organ pipes of the same length as open pipes sound an octave lower and are used for deep bass notes."
