        introduction: "In 1842, the Austrian physicist and mathematician Christian Andreas Doppler presented his theoretical prediction of the frequency shift produced by relative motion between a wave source and observer at the Royal Bohemian Society of Sciences in Prague, in his paper 'Über das farbige Licht der Doppelsterne' (On the Coloured Light of Double Stars). In 1845, the Dutch meteorologist Buijs-Ballot conducted the first experimental verification by having musicians play a single note on a moving train while stationary observers reported the perceived pitch.",

        aim: "The aim of Doppler's theoretical investigation was to derive the mathematical relationship between the frequency of a wave source moving relative to an observer and the frequency perceived by that observer — predicting that approach produces an upward frequency shift and recession produces a downward shift, with the magnitude depending on the ratio of source velocity to wave speed.",

        subject: "The subjects of Doppler's theoretical analysis were sound waves emitted by moving sources (trumpeters on a train carriage in Buijs-Ballot's experimental verification), with stationary observers comparing the perceived pitch against a reference note played by stationary musicians of the same type.",

        subjectDefinition: "The Doppler effect is the change in observed frequency of a wave when there is relative motion between the source and the observer. For a source moving at speed v_s towards a stationary observer through a medium where the wave travels at speed v: f_observed = f_source × v/(v − v_s). For recession: f_observed = f_source × v/(v + v_s). The frequency shift Δf = f_observed − f_source. For v_s << v (low Mach number), Δf ≈ ±f_source × v_s/v. The effect applies to all wave types — sound, light, water waves — wherever there is relative motion between source and observer.",

        results: "Buijs-Ballot's 1845 train experiment confirmed Doppler's predictions: musicians playing a constant note on a moving flatcar were heard by stationary observers as distinctly higher in pitch when approaching and lower when receding, with the shift consistent with Doppler's formula for train speeds of approximately 40–60 km/h. Doppler's effect was later recognised as universally applicable to all wave phenomena, including light (used in astronomy as the redshift/blueshift of stellar spectral lines to measure stellar and galactic motion).",

        modernConnection: "The data logger version of the Doppler experiment attaches a buzzer of fixed frequency to a string and swings it in a horizontal circle, or attaches it to a dynamics trolley moving along a track. A microphone connected to a data logger records the frequency variations as the buzzer alternately approaches and recedes. The recorded frequency trace shows the characteristic Doppler shift, and the source velocity can be calculated from the observed frequency changes using the Doppler formula."
