        subject: "The subjects of infrasound investigation were large-scale mechanical vibrators producing pure sub-20 Hz tones, pressure sensors and microbarometers measuring the resulting pressure oscillations, and human observers reporting physiological effects — the first systematic study of the human body's response to sub-audible sound.",

        subjectDefinition: "Infrasound is sound with a frequency below approximately 20 Hz — below the threshold of normal human hearing. Despite being inaudible (as a pitched sound), infrasound can be felt as pressure variations and causes physiological effects including disorientation, anxiety, visual disturbances, and resonance of internal organs at specific frequencies (e.g. the eyeball resonates near 18 Hz). Infrasound propagates with very little absorption over great distances: the absorption coefficient α decreases as 1/f², so infrasound from earthquakes, volcanoes, severe storms, and nuclear explosions can be detected thousands of kilometres from the source.",

