                hint: "f = (blades × RPM)/60.",
                answer: "Fundamental blade-pass frequency: f = (6 × 300)/60 = 30 Hz. This is just above infrasound range (but close to it; some fan components may operate at lower RPM and produce infrasound). Harmonics arise because the pressure pulse from each blade passing a fixed reference point (e.g. the housing) is not a perfect sinusoid but an impulse — a sharp pressure surge. By Fourier's theorem, any periodic non-sinusoidal waveform is composed of a fundamental plus harmonics at integer multiples (2f = 60 Hz, 3f = 90 Hz, etc.). Additionally, mechanical asymmetries between blades (slight differences in pitch, weight, or position) produce sub-harmonic and combination frequencies. The fundamental and its harmonics are all present in the radiated sound spectrum, which is why fan noise has a characteristic tonal quality at multiple frequencies."
