                hint: "This is an acoustic triangulation problem — similar to how earthquake epicentres are located from seismograph arrival times.",
                answer: "Infrasound travels at approximately the speed of sound in the atmosphere (300–340 m/s at altitude, affected by stratospheric temperature gradients). A nuclear explosion (or any large infrasound source) produces a strong signal detected by multiple stations at different times, depending on their distances from the source. Station A, closer to the source, detects the signal at time t_A; station B, further away, at t_B > t_A. The time difference Δt_AB = t_B − t_A combined with the known infrasound speed v gives: |r_B − r_A| = v × Δt_AB, which is the equation of a hyperbola in the plane containing both stations. A second pair of stations (B, C) gives another hyperbola. The intersection of the two hyperbolas locates the source. With three or more stations, the solution is over-determined — multiple hyperbola intersections must coincide, greatly improving location accuracy. The CTBTO network can locate large infrasound sources to within ±50–100 km worldwide."
