    category: 'waves_and_electromagnetic_spectrum',
    historicalBackground: {
        scientist: "James Clerk Maxwell",
        year: "1861–1873",

        introduction: "Between 1861 and 1873, the Scottish physicist James Clerk Maxwell developed the complete mathematical theory of electromagnetism at King's College London and later at Cambridge, unifying the previously separate phenomena of electricity and magnetism into four differential equations that predicted the existence of electromagnetic waves propagating at the speed of light — establishing that light itself is an electromagnetic wave.",

        aim: "The aim of Maxwell's theoretical investigation was to determine from the mathematical structure of his electromagnetic equations whether oscillating electric and magnetic fields could propagate as a self-sustaining wave in vacuum, predict the speed of this wave, and establish the fundamental properties (transverse nature, polarisation, energy transport) of such electromagnetic waves.",

        subject: "The subjects of Maxwell's analysis were the theoretical solutions to his field equations (now called Maxwell's equations) for sinusoidally varying electric and magnetic fields in free space, which he showed must be perpendicular to each other and to the direction of propagation, forming a transverse wave that travels at c = 1/√(ε₀μ₀) ≈ 3 × 10⁸ m/s.",

        subjectDefinition: "An electromagnetic wave is a transverse wave consisting of mutually perpendicular oscillating electric (E) and magnetic (B) fields, both perpendicular to the direction of propagation. The wave is self-sustaining: a changing E field generates a changing B field (Faraday's law), which in turn generates a changing E field (Ampere-Maxwell law), and so on — the fields regenerate each other in a chain extending through space. Polarisation refers to the orientation of the electric field vector. In a linearly polarised EM wave, E oscillates in a fixed plane; unpolarised waves have E oscillating in random directions. Malus's Law describes the transmitted intensity after a polariser: I = I₀cos²θ, where θ is the angle between the polariser axis and the incoming E field direction.",

        results: "Maxwell calculated that his electromagnetic waves would travel at c = 1/√(ε₀μ₀) = 1/√(8.85×10⁻¹²× 4π×10⁻⁷) = 2.998 × 10⁸ m/s — identical (within measurement error) to the known speed of light. He concluded that 'light is an electromagnetic disturbance propagated through the field according to electromagnetic laws.' Hertz experimentally confirmed the existence of radio waves (predicted by Maxwell) in 1888, demonstrating that they are indeed transverse, can be reflected, refracted, and polarised — all properties Maxwell had predicted from theory alone.",

        modernConnection: "The properties of EM waves predicted by Maxwell are demonstrated in the laboratory using microwave equipment, whose 2.8 cm wavelength makes polarisation effects easy to observe. A microwave transmitter emits linearly polarised microwaves (determined by the orientation of its horn antenna), and a receiver detects their intensity. Rotating the receiver by 90° tests for transverse polarisation; rotating by angle θ verifies Malus's Law; inserting a wire grid polariser between transmitter and receiver demonstrates polarisation and attenuation."
    },

