        introduction: "The theory of image formation by lenses was first developed by Ibn al-Haytham (Alhazen) in his 'Book of Optics' (1021), who correctly described the geometry of refraction through spherical surfaces. In 1267, the English friar Roger Bacon described the use of a convex glass lens as a magnifying glass and predicted spectacles — the first practical application of lens optics. The thin lens equation 1/f = 1/u + 1/v was formalised during the 17th century through the work of Kepler (1611) and Descartes (1637).",

        aim: "The aim of the early lens investigations was to derive the relationship between the position of an object, the position of its magnified or reduced image, and the focal length of a spherical glass lens — enabling the systematic design of optical instruments including telescopes, microscopes, spectacles, and cameras.",

        subject: "The subjects of early lens investigations were glass lenses of known curvature, with objects placed at measured distances and image positions determined by locating the screen position at which a sharp image formed — the same experimental protocol used in modern school laboratories today.",

        subjectDefinition: "A converging (convex) lens refracts parallel rays to converge at the principal focus F, located at distance f (the focal length) from the optical centre. The thin lens equation relates object distance u, image distance v, and focal length f: 1/f = 1/v + 1/u (real-is-positive convention: real objects u > 0, real images v > 0, virtual images v < 0). For a converging lens: objects beyond F produce real, inverted images on the far side; objects within F produce virtual, upright, magnified images on the same side as the object. Magnification m = v/u for real images and m = −v/u in the signed convention. The thin lens equation is identical in form to the mirror equation, reflecting a deep symmetry in first-order (paraxial) optics.",

        results: "The thin lens equation was systematically verified throughout the 17th–19th centuries by measuring u and v for converging and diverging lenses of measured focal lengths, confirming that 1/f = 1/u + 1/v holds for all object positions outside the focal length. The equation was foundational for the systematic design of optical instruments: Galileo designed his telescope using lens power combinations; Newton designed his reflecting telescope partly to avoid the chromatic aberration inherent in refracting lenses; and modern camera designers use the lens equation in combination with aberration theory to design complex multi-element objectives.",

        modernConnection: "The school converging lens experiment places a lens (focal length approximately 10–20 cm) on an optical bench and measures image distance v for a range of object distances u, plotting 1/v vs 1/u to verify the thin lens equation and determine the focal length graphically. This directly parallels the mirror experiment and provides a complete introduction to first-order geometrical optics."
