                answer: "Normal vision: the eye's natural lens (converging) can accommodate (change shape) to focus objects from the near point (≈ 25 cm for young adults) to infinity. With presbyopia, the lens stiffens and can only focus objects beyond ≈ 100 cm — print at 25–40 cm appears blurred. Reading glasses add converging power to the eye's optical system. The combined thin lens equation: 1/f_combined = 1/f_eye + 1/f_glasses. A reading glass of f = 50 cm (power +2 dioptres, D = 1/f in metres) adds converging power. When reading at u = 25 cm through these glasses: 1/v = 1/f_glasses − 1/u = 1/50 − 1/25 = −1/50, so v = −50 cm (virtual image, on the same side as the object). This virtual image is at 50 cm from the glasses — within the presbyopic eye's accommodation range. The glasses create a virtual image of the page at 50 cm, which the eye can then focus on, restoring comfortable reading at 25 cm."
