                answer: "A compound microscope has: (1) Objective lens (focal length f_obj ≈ 5–10 mm), close to the specimen. (2) Eyepiece lens (focal length f_eye ≈ 25 mm), through which the observer looks. The specimen is placed just beyond the objective's focal length, producing a real, inverted, magnified intermediate image at tube length L from the objective: m_obj = −v_obj/u_obj ≈ L/f_obj. This intermediate image acts as the object for the eyepiece, placed at the eyepiece's focal point — producing a virtual, further magnified image at infinity (comfortable for relaxed viewing): m_eye = D/f_eye (where D = 25 cm = near point distance). Total magnification: M_total = m_obj × m_eye ≈ (L/f_obj) × (D/f_eye). For a microscope with L = 160 mm, f_obj = 5 mm, f_eye = 25 mm, D = 250 mm: M = (160/5) × (250/25) = 32 × 10 = 320×. Modern research microscopes achieve magnifications of 1000–2000× using oil-immersion objectives."
