                answer: "Real image: formed at a point where light rays actually converge after refraction (or reflection). The light physically passes through the image point, so it can be caught on a screen placed there. Properties: always inverted (for a single thin converging lens with object beyond F), located on the opposite side of the lens from the object. Example: the image on a cinema screen is a real image — the film projector's lens refracts light to converge on the screen, which intercepts the real image and makes it visible by diffuse reflection. Virtual image: formed at a point where light rays appear to diverge from when extended backwards, but no light actually passes through that point. Cannot be caught on a screen. Properties: always upright (for a simple converging lens with object within F, or any single diverging lens), located on the same side of the lens as the object. Example: the image seen through a magnifying glass held close to a book — the lens creates a virtual, magnified image of the print that appears to be behind the lens, larger than the original. The eye receives diverging rays and perceives them as coming from the larger virtual image."
