        introduction: "In 1809, the French military engineer and physicist Étienne-Louis Malus discovered the phenomenon of polarisation by reflection while observing sunlight reflected in windows of the Luxembourg Palace in Paris, using a calcite crystal (Iceland spar) as an analyser — and subsequently formulated the quantitative law governing transmitted intensity through a polarising filter.",

        aim: "The aim of his investigation was to determine the mathematical relationship between the angle of a polarising analyser relative to the plane of polarisation of incident light and the intensity of the transmitted beam — establishing whether intensity follows a simple trigonometric law.",

        subject: "The subjects of Malus's investigation were beams of polarised light (initially polarised by reflection off glass surfaces) passing through a calcite birefringent crystal rotated to various angles, with transmitted intensity judged by eye comparison.",

        subjectDefinition: "Polarisation is a property of transverse waves in which the oscillation of the wave's displacement is confined to a single plane (plane polarisation). For light (an electromagnetic wave), polarisation refers to the orientation of the electric field vector. Unpolarised light contains oscillations in all planes perpendicular to the direction of travel. A polaroid filter transmits only the component of the electric field parallel to its transmission axis, converting unpolarised light to plane-polarised light. When polarised light of intensity I₀ passes through a second polaroid (analyser) whose transmission axis makes angle θ with the polarisation direction, Malus's Law states that the transmitted intensity is I = I₀cos²(θ).",

        results: "Malus found that the transmitted intensity varies as the square of the cosine of the angle between the polariser and analyser — the relationship now known as Malus's Law: I = I₀cos²(θ). At θ = 0° (parallel filters), full intensity is transmitted; at θ = 90° (crossed filters), transmission falls to zero. He published these results in 1809, winning the prize of the Institut de France and establishing that light is a transverse wave phenomenon.",

        modernConnection: "Malus's Law is verified in the investigation below using two polaroid sheets and a light sensor (LDR or photodiode). Students rotate the analyser through measured angles and record transmitted intensity, then plot I against cos²(θ) to confirm the linear relationship — replicating Malus's 1809 discovery with modern electronic sensors instead of eye comparison."
