        introduction: "In the 1870s, the Austrian physicist Ernst Mach developed the ripple tank as a systematic laboratory apparatus for visualising the behaviour of water surface waves, using stroboscopic illumination to freeze moving wave patterns and project them onto a viewing screen — transforming wave phenomena from abstract concepts into directly observable geometric patterns.",

        aim: "The aim of his investigations was to demonstrate that wave phenomena — reflection, refraction, diffraction, and interference — obey precise geometric and mathematical laws, and that water surface waves provide a physical analogue for studying light, sound, and all other wave types in a directly visible medium.",

