        subjectDefinition: "A ripple tank is a shallow glass-bottomed container of water used to demonstrate wave behaviour. Waves are generated by motorised dippers or vibrating wires. Reflection occurs when waves bounce off barriers, following the law of reflection (angle of incidence equals angle of reflection). Refraction occurs when waves pass from deep to shallow water — their speed decreases in shallow water, causing the wavefronts to bend toward the normal. Diffraction occurs when waves pass through gaps or around obstacles — wavefronts spread into the geometric shadow, with the extent of spreading dependent on the ratio of wavelength to gap size.",

        results: "Mach found that water waves in a ripple tank obey the same geometric laws as light: straight barriers produce specular reflection; shallow-water regions refract wavefronts toward the normal as wave speed decreases; gaps and edges produce diffraction spreading that increases as gap width decreases or wavelength increases. He used these demonstrations to argue by analogy for the wave nature of light, and the ripple tank became a standard physics teaching tool that remains in use today.",

        modernConnection: "The ripple tank investigation below replicates Mach's demonstrations: students observe and measure reflection angles, identify refraction as waves cross a depth boundary, and observe diffraction spreading through gaps of varying width — directly visualising the wave behaviours that govern light, sound, and all electromagnetic radiation."
