        subjectDefinition: "The Doppler effect is the change in observed frequency of a wave caused by relative motion between the wave source and the observer. When the source moves toward the observer, successive wavefronts are compressed into a shorter distance — the observer receives them more frequently, perceiving a higher pitch. When the source moves away, wavefronts are stretched — the observer perceives a lower pitch. For a source moving at speed v_s and sound travelling at speed v, the observed frequency is f_obs = f_source × v / (v ∓ v_s), where the minus sign applies when the source approaches and the plus sign when it recedes.",

        results: "Buys Ballot confirmed Doppler's prediction: the pitch heard from the approaching train was consistently higher than the true note, and the pitch heard from the receding train was lower — by amounts quantitatively consistent with the Doppler formula. The experiment established the Doppler effect as a real, measurable phenomenon applicable to all wave types including sound and, by extension, light (redshift and blueshift in astronomy).",

