                answer: "When a source emits sound, it produces wavefronts at regular intervals set by its emission frequency. If the source is stationary, each successive wavefront is emitted from the same position, so the wavefronts are evenly spaced in all directions. When the source moves toward the observer, by the time it emits the next wavefront, it has moved closer to the observer than it was when it emitted the previous one. Each subsequent wavefront is emitted from a position closer to the observer, so the distance between adjacent wavefronts in the forward direction is compressed — the wavelength is shorter in the direction of motion. Since wave speed in the medium (air) is unchanged, a shorter wavelength means the observer receives wavefronts more frequently — the observed frequency is higher than the emission frequency. The opposite happens for a receding source: wavefronts are stretched apart, wavelength is longer, observed frequency is lower."
