        aim: "The aim of Hertz's investigations was to demonstrate that electromagnetic waves could be generated, reflected, and made to form standing waves in air, and by measuring the positions of nodes and antinodes, to determine their wavelength — establishing that electromagnetic waves obey the same phase and interference principles as sound and water waves.",

        subject: "The subjects of Hertz's experiment were electromagnetic waves generated by an oscillating spark discharge and detected at varying distances by a resonating loop detector, with the phase of oscillation in the detector varying with position relative to a reflecting wall.",

        subjectDefinition: "Phase difference is the difference in the stage of oscillation between two points in a wave at a given moment in time, measured in degrees or radians. Two points oscillating in phase (phase difference = 0° or 2πn) reach their maxima and minima simultaneously. Two points exactly out of phase (phase difference = 180° or π) reach opposite extremes simultaneously. Phase difference between two positions in a wave is related to path difference by: phase difference (radians) = (2π/λ) × path difference. An oscilloscope with two inputs (dual channel) can display two waveforms simultaneously, allowing direct visual comparison of their phases.",

        results: "Hertz found that his detector showed alternating maximum and minimum response at positions consistent with standing wave nodes and antinodes, confirming that electromagnetic waves could interfere and produce predictable phase relationships with position. The measured wavelength (~66 cm) matched the theoretical prediction from the oscillator frequency, confirming the wave nature of electromagnetic radiation and foreshadowing radio communication.",

        modernConnection: "The investigation below applies Hertz's phase-comparison approach to sound waves: two microphones placed at different positions from a single speaker are connected to a dual-channel oscilloscope. The phase difference between the two channels changes as one microphone is moved, allowing direct measurement of wavelength and the relationship between path difference and phase — the same physics Hertz used to characterise electromagnetic waves."
