        subjectDefinition: "A diffraction grating is an optical surface ruled with thousands of equally spaced parallel slits or grooves per millimetre. When coherent light of wavelength λ passes through the grating, each slit acts as a new wave source (by Huygens' principle), and the diffracted waves from all slits interfere constructively only at specific angles θ given by the grating equation: nλ = d sin(θ), where n is the order number (n = 0, 1, 2, ...), d is the slit spacing (= 1/number of lines per metre), and θ is the angle of the nth-order maximum. The grating equation allows wavelength to be calculated from a precision angle measurement.",

