            {
                question: "Derive the grating equation nλ = d sin(θ) from first principles using the condition for constructive interference between adjacent slits.",
                hint: "For constructive interference, the path difference between waves from adjacent slits must be an integer number of wavelengths.",
                answer: "Consider two adjacent slits separated by distance d (the grating spacing). For waves diffracted at angle θ from the normal, the extra path travelled by the wave from the more distant slit is d sin(θ) — this is the geometric path difference for adjacent slits. For constructive interference (bright maximum), this path difference must equal an integer multiple of the wavelength: d sin(θ) = nλ, where n = 0, 1, 2, ... is the order number. At n = 0, θ = 0 — the straight-through central maximum. At n = 1, the first-order maximum occurs at sin(θ) = λ/d. This condition applies simultaneously to all pairs of adjacent slits in the grating — the thousands of slits reinforce the constructive interference, making the maxima very sharp and bright compared to a two-slit pattern."
            },
            {
                question: "A diffraction grating has 500 lines/mm. Calculate the maximum order of diffraction visible for a red laser (λ = 650 nm).",
                hint: "For the maximum order, sin(θ) must not exceed 1 (i.e. θ ≤ 90°). Set sin(θ) = 1 in the grating equation.",
                answer: "Grating spacing: d = 1/500 lines per mm = 1/500,000 lines per m = 2.0 × 10⁻⁶ m = 2000 nm. Maximum order when sin(θ) = 1: n_max = d/λ = 2000/650 ≈ 3.08. Since n must be a whole number and sin(θ) ≤ 1, the maximum observable order is n = 3. The 3rd-order maximum is at sin(θ) = 3 × 650/2000 = 0.975, giving θ = arcsin(0.975) ≈ 77°. A 4th-order maximum would require sin(θ) = 4 × 650/2000 = 1.30 > 1, which is physically impossible. With a finer grating (more lines/mm, smaller d), fewer orders are accessible because d becomes comparable to λ — the first-order maximum already appears at a large angle."
            },
            {
                question: "A student uses a grating and white light (not a laser) and observes coloured spectra on either side of the central white maximum. Explain why the colours appear in a specific order and why violet light is closer to the centre than red light in each order.",
                hint: "Use nλ = d sin(θ) and consider how θ depends on λ for a given order n.",
                answer: "For a given order n and grating spacing d, the grating equation gives sin(θ) = nλ/d. Since sin(θ) is directly proportional to λ, longer wavelengths are diffracted to larger angles. Violet light (λ ≈ 400 nm) is diffracted to a smaller angle than red light (λ ≈ 700 nm). Therefore, in each spectrum on either side of the central maximum, violet appears closest to the centre (smallest θ) and red appears furthest from the centre (largest θ). This is the opposite dispersion order to a prism, where red refracts least (also smallest deviation from straight-through), but the reasons differ: in a grating, longer λ gives larger diffraction angle; in a prism, shorter λ gives greater refraction (because the refractive index is higher for shorter wavelengths due to dispersion)."
            },
            {
                question: "Why is a diffraction grating able to measure wavelengths far more precisely than a single double-slit, even though both use the same interference principle?",
                hint: "Think about what happens to the sharpness of maxima when the number of slits increases from 2 to thousands.",
                answer: "In a two-slit setup, the interference maxima are broad — the intensity distribution is a cosine-squared pattern spread over a wide range of angles. The uncertainty in locating the peak angle is large, giving a large uncertainty in wavelength. A diffraction grating uses thousands of slits simultaneously. All slits contribute constructively only at the precise angle satisfying nλ = d sin(θ) — at all other angles, the large number of slits ensures near-perfect destructive interference (the many phases add to nearly zero). The result is that grating maxima are extremely sharp and narrow, with broad dark regions between them. The sharpness of the maximum means its angular position can be located with very high precision, translating into very precise wavelength measurements. The resolving power of a grating increases as N × n (N = number of illuminated slits, n = order) — a grating with 10,000 illuminated slits can resolve wavelengths differing by less than 0.06 nm in first order."
            },
            {
                question: "In this experiment, the laser beam must be incident perpendicular to the grating. Explain what happens to the diffraction pattern if the laser is tilted slightly and how this introduces a systematic error in wavelength measurement.",
                hint: "Consider how the path difference between adjacent slits changes when the incident beam is not normal to the grating surface.",
                answer: "When the laser is incident at angle α to the grating normal (not perpendicular), the modified grating equation becomes: d(sin θ + sin α) = nλ, where θ is measured from the grating normal. If α is incorrectly assumed to be zero, the calculation uses sin(θ_apparent) = nλ/d rather than the correct equation. This shifts all measured diffraction angles away from their true values. The error is systematic — all measurements in one direction are shifted by the same angular offset. The effect is asymmetric: the left and right first-order maxima will no longer be equal distances from the apparent centre on the screen. A student can check for this error by measuring both left and right maxima separately — if they give different values of sin(θ) for the same order, the grating is not perpendicular to the beam. The symmetric average of left and right reduces but does not completely eliminate this error."
            },
            {
                question: "Fraunhofer used his grating to discover the dark absorption lines in the solar spectrum (Fraunhofer lines). Explain why the solar spectrum contains dark lines at specific wavelengths and what these lines reveal about the composition of the Sun.",
                hint: "Consider what happens when light from the hot solar interior passes through the cooler solar atmosphere.",
                answer: "The Sun's interior produces a continuous spectrum of thermal radiation at all wavelengths (blackbody radiation). As this white light passes through the Sun's cooler outer atmosphere (photosphere and chromosphere), atoms in the atmosphere absorb photons at specific wavelengths corresponding to electronic transitions in those atoms. Hydrogen atoms absorb at 656 nm (Hα), 486 nm (Hβ), etc.; sodium atoms absorb at 589 nm (D lines); calcium at 393 nm and 397 nm, and so on. After the atoms absorb photons they re-emit them in random directions, so very little of the absorbed light continues toward Earth in the original direction — the spectrum shows dark absorption lines at those wavelengths. By measuring the precise wavelengths of the Fraunhofer lines with a grating spectrometer, astronomers can identify which elements are present in the solar atmosphere, their abundances, and even their temperatures and pressures from line widths — giving detailed information about solar composition without any physical sample."
            }
