        introduction: "In 1916–1917, the French physicist Paul Langevin developed the first practical sonar (Sound Navigation And Ranging) system in response to the threat of submarine warfare during World War I — using piezoelectric quartz transducers to generate ultrasonic pulses and detect their echoes returning from submerged objects, thereby measuring distances by the pulse-echo time method.",

