        subjectDefinition: "Sonar (Sound Navigation And Ranging) is a technique that uses the propagation and reflection of sound waves to measure distance and detect objects in water. A sonar system emits a pulse of sound and records the time t until the echo returns. The distance d to the reflecting object is calculated from d = v × t/2, where v is the speed of sound in water (~1500 m/s) and the factor of 2 accounts for the two-way travel (to the object and back). This pulse-echo principle is also used by bats (echolocation), medical ultrasound imaging, and radar.",

        results: "Langevin's sonar system successfully detected submarines at distances of several kilometres and measured seafloor depths reliably. It demonstrated that the pulse-echo method converts a time measurement (easy and precise) into a distance measurement, with accuracy limited by the precision of the timing and knowledge of the sound speed in the medium. The same principle was later extended to medical ultrasound, acoustic depth-sounding, bat echolocation research, and eventually radar.",

        modernConnection: "The investigation below simulates the sonar pulse-echo method using sound pulses transmitted between a speaker and microphone: students generate short sound pulses, record the echo from a nearby wall or reflector, measure the time delay, and calculate the distance — verifying d = vt/2 against a tape-measure distance. This directly models Langevin's underwater ranging system at human audible frequencies and laboratory distances."
