                answer: "The sound pulse must travel from the transmitter to the reflector (distance d) and then return from the reflector to the receiver (distance d again) — a total path of 2d. The time measured t is the total travel time for this round trip: t = 2d/v. Rearranging gives d = vt/2. The factor of 2 accounts for the two-way journey. If d = vt were used (ignoring the factor of 2), all calculated distances would be twice the actual distance — a systematic error of factor 2. This two-way path principle applies identically to sonar (sound in water), radar (microwaves in air), and medical ultrasound (sound in tissue)."
