                answer: "Distance: d = vt/2 = 1520 × 2.4/2 = 1520 × 1.2 = 1824 m ≈ 1.82 km. Sources of uncertainty: (1) Uncertainty in wave speed: the speed of sound in seawater varies with temperature, salinity, and depth (pressure). A variation of 30 m/s (2%) in v translates directly to a 2% error in distance (~36 m at this range). Real sonar systems use sound velocity profilers to measure v continuously with depth. (2) Timing precision: the echo pulse has a finite duration, making precise identification of the echo arrival time uncertain. If the echo duration is 10 ms, the timing uncertainty is ~5 ms (half the pulse), corresponding to a distance uncertainty of 1520 × 0.005/2 = 3.8 m. Shorter pulses improve timing precision but reduce energy, weakening the echo — another fundamental trade-off in pulse design."
