                answer: "Wavelength at 50 kHz: λ = v/f = 340/50,000 = 0.0068 m = 6.8 mm. This is comparable to the size of the insects bats prey on (5–20 mm body length, 1–5 mm wing thickness). An object reflects sound effectively only when its size is greater than approximately λ/2 — objects much smaller than the wavelength cause only negligible scattering. At 50 kHz (λ = 6.8 mm), a 10 mm moth wing reflects the pulse effectively — the bat receives a detectable echo. At human hearing frequencies (~1 kHz, λ = 340 mm), a 10 mm moth would be invisible — the wavelength is 34 times larger than the target. Bats evolved ultrasonic echolocation precisely because the short wavelengths at these frequencies are appropriate for detecting small, fast-moving insects. Different bat species use different peak frequencies calibrated to the size of their preferred prey."
