                hint: "Two objects can only be separated if their echoes do not overlap in time.",
                answer: "If a sound pulse has duration τ, the echo from an object spans the same duration τ in time. If a second object is located at a slightly greater distance, its echo arrives at a slightly later time. The two echoes can only be distinguished as separate if the second echo begins after the first echo has completely ended — i.e., the time difference between echo arrivals must exceed τ. Since the time difference for two objects separated by Δd is Δt = 2Δd/v, the minimum resolvable separation is: Δd_min = vτ/2. For τ = 1 ms and v = 340 m/s: Δd_min = 340 × 0.001/2 = 0.17 m = 17 cm. Two objects closer together than 17 cm cannot be distinguished — their echoes overlap. To achieve 1 cm resolution, the pulse duration must be reduced to τ = 2 × 0.01/340 ≈ 0.059 ms — which requires transmitting at higher frequency (shorter period). This is why medical ultrasound uses very short, high-frequency pulses to achieve millimetre resolution."
