                question: "Explain using the superposition principle why nodes are points of permanent zero displacement in a standing wave.",
                hint: "At a node, the incident and reflected waves always have equal and opposite displacements — show why this is the case at all times.",
                answer: "The incident wave can be written as y₁ = A sin(kx − ωt) and the reflected wave (reflected from a fixed end, with a phase inversion) as y₂ = −A sin(kx + ωt). By superposition, the total displacement is y = y₁ + y₂ = A sin(kx − ωt) − A sin(kx + ωt). Using the identity sin(P) − sin(Q) = 2cos((P+Q)/2)sin((P−Q)/2): y = −2A cos(kx) sin(ωt). At positions where cos(kx) = 0, i.e. kx = π/2, 3π/2, ..., or x = λ/4, 3λ/4, ..., the displacement y = 0 for all times t — these are the nodes. At these positions, the incident and reflected waves always have exactly equal and opposite displacements at every instant, so they always cancel by destructive superposition. The zero displacement at nodes is not a coincidence at one moment but a permanent structural feature of the interference pattern."
