        year: "1859",

        introduction: "In 1859, the German physicist Franz Emil Melde performed a landmark series of experiments at the University of Marburg in which he attached strings to the prong of a tuning fork and observed stationary wave patterns formed at various tensions — systematically determining the quantitative relationship between string tension, vibration frequency, string length, and the number of loops in the resulting standing wave.",

        aim: "The aim of Melde's investigation was to verify experimentally the theoretical predictions of Mersenne's Laws — specifically, that the frequency of vibration is proportional to the square root of tension and inversely proportional to both the string length and the square root of linear density — by using a fixed-frequency tuning fork as his driver and observing how the loop count changed as he varied the tension.",

        subject: "The subjects of Melde's experiments were long, light strings attached to a vibrating tuning fork prong at one end and passing over a pulley with calibrated hanging masses at the other, observed under stroboscopic candlelight to reveal the stationary wave patterns at varying tensions.",

        subjectDefinition: "Melde's experiment is a quantitative investigation of stationary waves on a string in which the driving frequency is fixed (by a tuning fork or signal generator) and the tension is varied. Since f = nv/(2L) = n√(T/μ)/(2L), and f is fixed, the number of loops n changes with tension: n = 2Lf/v = 2Lf√(μ/T). Increasing tension at fixed frequency decreases n (fewer, longer loops); decreasing tension increases n (more, shorter loops). The relationship n²T = constant (at fixed f, L, μ) provides a precise verification of the tension-frequency-wavelength relationships in string vibrations.",

        results: "Melde found that the number of loops in the standing wave pattern changed predictably with tension, consistent with the theoretical relationship n ∝ 1/√T at fixed frequency. He verified that the wavelength (loop length × 2) changed inversely with loop count, and that wave speed v = fλ remained constant for a given tension. His work provided strong quantitative confirmation of Mersenne's Laws and established the canonical laboratory method for studying standing waves on strings with controlled parameters.",

