                answer: "Advantage of tuning fork: extremely stable, precise frequency — a high-quality tuning fork maintains its frequency to within a fraction of a hertz throughout its vibration, unaffected by temperature or electrical fluctuations. Its frequency is determined by its physical dimensions (mass and elasticity) and is essentially fixed — it cannot drift. Disadvantage: fixed, non-adjustable frequency — the tuning fork can only provide its single stamped frequency (e.g. 440 Hz). Repeating the experiment at different frequencies requires physically different tuning forks. A signal generator can be continuously adjusted across a wide frequency range, allowing the experiment to be performed at any desired frequency and making it straightforward to investigate how the resonant tensions change with driving frequency. Additionally, a tuning fork excites the string by direct mechanical contact of its prong, which slightly loads the fork and can affect its frequency; a signal generator through a transducer provides controlled, electrical coupling."
