        introduction: "In 1866, the German physicist August Kundt published a precise method for measuring the speed of sound in gases and solids using a glass tube partially filled with a fine powder — now known as Kundt's tube — in which standing sound waves were established at known frequencies, and the positions of the powder at the nodes were used to measure wavelength with high precision.",

        aim: "The aim of Kundt's investigation was to develop a precision laboratory method for measuring the speed of sound in various media (gases, liquids, solids) from direct measurements of the wavelength of standing waves at known frequency — overcoming the limitations of timing methods over long distances that had been used previously.",

        subject: "The subjects of Kundt's experiments were standing sound waves in gas-filled glass tubes excited at known frequencies by a vibrating rod or speaker, visualised by fine lycopodium powder or cork dust that accumulated at the velocity nodes (pressure antinodes) of the standing wave, revealing the wavelength directly from the node spacing.",

        subjectDefinition: "A resonance tube is a tube open at one or both ends in which sound waves can resonate when the tube length matches the resonance condition for the driving frequency. For a closed-open tube, resonance occurs when L = (2n−1)λ/4 for n = 1, 2, 3... — the tube length must be an odd number of quarter-wavelengths. For an open-open tube, L = nλ/2. By filling a cylindrical tube with water (acting as a movable closed end) and driving it with a tuning fork or speaker of known frequency, the tube length can be adjusted until resonance occurs, the resonant length measured, and the wavelength calculated — giving the speed of sound from v = fλ.",

        results: "Kundt measured the speed of sound in several gases with precision better than 1% and in solids from the ratio of wavelengths in solid and gas in the same tube. He demonstrated that sound speed varies with gas composition, temperature, and pressure in predictable ways. His tube method became the standard laboratory technique for precision sound speed measurements and is still replicated in school and university physics laboratories today in the form of the resonance tube experiment.",

        modernConnection: "The investigation below uses a water-filled resonance tube (closed-open configuration) driven by a tuning fork or speaker: students vary the water level to find the tube length at which resonance (maximum loudness) occurs for each harmonic, measure the resonant lengths, and calculate the speed of sound — using the same standing wave principle as Kundt's powder tube, implemented with a water column as an adjustable closed end."
