        introduction: "In 1877, the English physicist John William Strutt (Lord Rayleigh) published The Theory of Sound, in which he provided the first rigorous mathematical treatment of standing waves — demonstrating analytically that a standing wave, formed by the superposition of two identical waves travelling in opposite directions, carries zero net energy flux in either direction, in striking contrast to a travelling wave which carries energy continuously in its direction of propagation.",

        aim: "The aim of Rayleigh's analysis was to calculate the instantaneous power flow (energy flux) in a standing wave and demonstrate mathematically that the time-averaged energy transport is exactly zero — because the energy contributions of the two constituent travelling waves cancel precisely when averaged over a full cycle, trapping energy in local oscillations at antinodes rather than transporting it.",

        subject: "The subject of Rayleigh's investigation was the mathematical structure of standing wave solutions to the wave equation, specifically the analysis of energy density distribution and energy flow (Poynting vector analogue for mechanical waves) in both travelling and standing wave configurations.",

        subjectDefinition: "A travelling wave transports energy from source to receiver: energy flows in the direction of wave propagation at a rate proportional to amplitude squared and wave speed. A standing wave, by contrast, stores energy locally — potential energy at nodes (maximum curvature, zero velocity) and kinetic energy at antinodes (maximum velocity, zero curvature) — but the net flow of energy along the wave direction averages to zero over any complete cycle. This is because a standing wave is the superposition of two identical waves travelling in opposite directions; their individual energy fluxes are equal and opposite, summing to zero.",

        results: "Rayleigh proved analytically that the time-averaged energy flux (Poynting vector equivalent) in a standing wave is identically zero everywhere — energy oscillates back and forth between adjacent quarter-wavelength sections but does not accumulate or drain from any region on average. He also showed that the total energy in each half-wavelength section oscillates between entirely kinetic (antinode at maximum velocity) and entirely potential (node at maximum curvature), with the total always constant. This is why standing waves in strings, pipes, and cavities can sustain oscillations indefinitely in the absence of damping — they store energy without dissipating it.",

        modernConnection: "The investigation below demonstrates the energy-trapping character of standing waves using a vibrating string: students observe that placing an energy absorber (a small strip of tissue paper) at a node produces no damping effect (no energy arrives at the node), while the same absorber at an antinode rapidly damps the vibration — directly demonstrating that energy is concentrated at antinodes and absent at nodes, with no net energy flow past the nodes."
