                hint: "Kinetic energy ∝ (velocity)². Potential energy ∝ (displacement)². Use y = 2A cos(kx) sin(ωt) to identify when velocity and displacement are maximum.",
                answer: "Displacement: y = 2A cos(kx) sin(ωt) — maximum when sin(ωt) = 1, i.e. ωt = π/2. Velocity: ∂y/∂t = 2Aω cos(kx) cos(ωt) — maximum when cos(ωt) = 1, i.e. ωt = 0. At ωt = 0 (zero displacement, maximum velocity): all energy is kinetic — the string is horizontal but every point is moving at maximum speed. At ωt = π/2 (maximum displacement, zero velocity): all energy is potential — the string is at maximum curvature and every point is momentarily stationary. The total energy oscillates between entirely kinetic (at ωt = 0, π) and entirely potential (at ωt = π/2, 3π/2) — a perfect periodic exchange between the two forms. This is the 'local oscillation' of energy between kinetic and potential, with no net spatial transport."
