    subjectDefinition: "An oscilloscope is an electronic instrument that displays voltage (or a proportional signal) on the vertical axis against time on the horizontal axis. In modern dual-channel oscilloscopes, two signals can be displayed simultaneously for comparison. When connected to a microphone, an oscilloscope displays the instantaneous air pressure variation at the microphone's position as a function of time — effectively measuring the local amplitude of a sound wave. By scanning a microphone along a standing wave while monitoring the oscilloscope, the spatial variation of amplitude (maximum displacement at antinodes, zero at nodes) can be mapped directly.",

