introduction: "In 1887–1888, the German physicist Heinrich Hertz performed the landmark experiments at Karlsruhe that demonstrated the existence of electromagnetic waves — first generating them with a spark oscillator, then proving they could be reflected and made to form standing waves by measuring the positions of maxima and minima in the field between the transmitter and a metal reflector, thereby measuring their wavelength and confirming Maxwell's prediction of electromagnetic wave propagation.",

    aim: "The aim of Hertz's investigation was to demonstrate that electromagnetic waves exhibit the same properties as light waves — including reflection, refraction, interference, and standing wave formation — thereby confirming Maxwell's electromagnetic theory and establishing that light is an electromagnetic wave.",

    subject: "The subjects of Hertz's experiments were electromagnetic waves at a frequency of approximately 450 MHz (wavelength ~66 cm) generated by a spark-gap oscillator and detected by a resonating loop receiver at varying distances from a metal reflector, with the detector signal varying between maximum and minimum as nodes and antinodes were traversed.",

    subjectDefinition: "Microwave standing waves are formed when microwave radiation (electromagnetic waves at GHz frequencies, wavelength ~cm) is reflected from a metal surface. The incident and reflected waves superpose to create fixed nodes (where field is always zero) and antinodes (where field oscillates at maximum amplitude). Since microwaves have wavelengths of a few centimetres, the node-antinode spacing (λ/2) is easily measurable with a ruler. A microwave detector (diode probe) placed at varying positions along the standing wave produces an output voltage proportional to field intensity, allowing direct mapping of the spatial amplitude pattern.",

    results: "Hertz found that the positions of maximum and minimum detector response alternated periodically as he moved the detector between transmitter and reflector, with a spacing of approximately 33 cm — half the wavelength of his microwave oscillator at approximately 66 cm. This directly demonstrated standing electromagnetic waves and allowed the first laboratory measurement of electromagnetic wavelength, confirming that the wave speed (calculated from f × λ) matched the speed of light — the decisive verification of Maxwell's theory.",

    modernConnection: "The investigation below replicates Hertz's standing wave measurement at microwave frequencies (typically ~10 GHz, λ ≈ 3 cm) using modern Gunn diode microwave transmitters, metal reflectors, and diode detector probes. Students scan the detector along the standing wave axis and record signal strength vs position, measuring node-antinode spacing to determine wavelength and compare to the known microwave frequency."
