introduction: "In 1801, the English polymath Thomas Young demonstrated the principle of superposition of waves through his celebrated double-slit light experiment — showing that two overlapping waves can either reinforce (constructive interference, producing bright fringes) or cancel (destructive interference, producing dark fringes) depending on their path difference, thereby establishing the principle of superposition as fundamental to all wave phenomena.",

    aim: "The aim of Young's investigation was to demonstrate that light behaves as a wave rather than as particles — by showing that two beams of light from the same source, passing through two closely spaced slits, produce an alternating pattern of bright and dark regions rather than the two bright patches predicted by a particle (corpuscular) theory.",

