            answer: "By Huygens' principle, each point across the slit width a acts as a secondary wave source. Consider the first minimum: it occurs at the angle θ where contributions from different parts of the slit cancel exactly. Divide the slit into two halves. For each source in the top half, there is a corresponding source in the bottom half that is exactly a/2 away. At angle θ, the path difference between paired sources (separated by a/2) is (a/2)sin(θ). For destructive interference between each pair, this path difference must equal λ/2: (a/2)sin(θ) = λ/2, giving sin(θ) = λ/a. The central maximum spans from −θ to +θ. For the small-angle approximation, the half-width on screen is approximately θD = λD/a, so the full central maximum width W = 2λD/a. Since W ∝ 1/a, halving the slit width doubles the central maximum width. Wider slits cause paired sources to be further apart — the angle needed for destructive interference is smaller, giving a narrower central maximum closer to the geometric shadow edge."
