            answer: "(a) Infinitely narrow slit: As a → 0, the first minimum angle sin(θ) = λ/a → ∞, meaning there is no minimum at finite angle — the entire screen is uniformly bright in all directions. This is because a point source (infinitely narrow slit) emits Huygens secondary waves equally in all directions (spherical/circular waves). The 'diffraction pattern' is completely uniform — the central maximum has expanded to fill the entire hemisphere. In practice, any slit smaller than approximately λ/2 acts essentially as a single Huygens point source. (b) Infinitely wide slit: As a → ∞, the first minimum angle sin(θ) = λ/a → 0, meaning the first minimum occurs at zero angle from the centre — the entire screen except the direct central line is dark. This is the geometric optics limit: no diffraction, just a sharp shadow of the slit edges. An infinitely wide slit passes all the light straight through with no angular spreading. In practice, when a >> λ (slit much larger than wavelength), diffraction is negligible except very close to the geometric shadow edge — explaining why everyday light sources cast sharp shadows even though diffraction is real."
