                answer: "An open system exchanges both matter and energy across its boundary — example: a car engine (fuel in, exhaust gases out, heat and work both transferred). A closed system exchanges energy but not matter — example: a sealed pressure cooker (no matter escapes, but heat enters from the stove). An isolated system exchanges neither energy nor matter — example: an ideal calorimeter bomb used in thermochemistry experiments (in practice, only approximately isolated). Real isolated systems are theoretical constructs; the universe as a whole is often cited as the only truly isolated system."
