                answer: "The claim is incorrect. An ideal isolated system prevents energy transfer across its boundary, meaning ΔU = 0 and the total internal energy is conserved — but this does not mean the water stays at exactly 80°C. In practice, no thermos is perfectly isolated: small amounts of heat escape through the stopper and residual conduction through the glass walls. Furthermore, even inside a perfectly isolated system, spontaneous irreversible processes occur — including mixing, redistribution of thermal energy among molecules, and (over time) equilibration of any temperature gradients within the water. These internal processes increase entropy without changing total internal energy. The claim also ignores that the water and trapped air above it will reach mutual thermal equilibrium internally — energy is redistributed within the system but none crosses the boundary. A real thermos maintains near-constant temperature but never exactly constant, always losing small amounts of energy to the environment."
