                answer: "A sealed cylinder with a movable piston: no matter crosses the boundary (sealed) — closed system. No heat transfer occurs (the problem states this, i.e. adiabatic process) — Q = 0. The piston does work ON the gas: mechanical energy from the piston crosses the boundary as work. By convention, W > 0 means work done BY the system on surroundings. Here, work is done on the system (compression), so W < 0 (negative work done by the system). Applying the First Law: ΔU = Q − W = 0 − (negative value) = positive value. Therefore ΔU > 0 — the internal energy of the gas increases, which manifests as a temperature increase. This is why a bicycle pump gets warm when you pump it rapidly: adiabatic compression raises the internal energy and temperature of the air."
