        aim: "The aim of formalising the Zeroth Law was to establish the logical basis of thermometry itself: to prove that the concept of 'temperature' as a consistent, measurable property of matter is only valid if the transitive property of thermal equilibrium holds — that is, if two systems are each in thermal equilibrium with a third, they must be in thermal equilibrium with each other.",

        subject: "The subject of the Zeroth Law is the concept of thermal equilibrium between thermodynamic systems — the state in which no net heat flows between bodies when they are in thermal contact, which Fowler and his contemporaries recognised as the precondition for defining temperature as an objective, consistent measurable quantity.",

        subjectDefinition: "Thermal equilibrium is the condition in which two or more bodies in thermal contact reach the same temperature and experience no further net transfer of heat. The Zeroth Law states: if body A is in thermal equilibrium with body C, and body B is in thermal equilibrium with body C, then A and B are in thermal equilibrium with each other. This law is called the 'zeroth' because it was formulated after the First and Second Laws but is logically prior to both — temperature cannot be defined without it. It is the theoretical justification for all thermometers: a thermometer reads the temperature of a body because it reaches thermal equilibrium with it, and two bodies reading the same thermometer value are therefore in equilibrium with each other.",

        results: "Fowler's formalisation of the Zeroth Law was a conceptual rather than experimental contribution — it codified what every experimental physicist had assumed but never explicitly stated. The practical consequence is that temperature is a valid, transitive, objective property: if two objects independently reach the same temperature (as measured by a thermometer), placing them in contact results in no heat flow. Every thermometer ever used relies on this principle.",

        modernConnection: "The Zeroth Law is the foundation of all temperature measurement. The investigation below verifies it directly: students bring three objects to different temperatures, measure each with a thermometer, then bring them into mutual contact to verify that equilibrium is reached and that the thermometer correctly predicts which pairs will exchange heat. Students also verify the transitivity principle by using one object as a 'third body' reference.",

