                answer: "The Zeroth Law states: if body A is in thermal equilibrium with body C, and body B is in thermal equilibrium with body C, then body A is in thermal equilibrium with body B. It is called the 'zeroth' law because it was formally articulated after the First and Second Laws had already been numbered, but its content is logically more fundamental than either — the First Law uses the concept of temperature (via internal energy), and the Second Law uses temperature in defining entropy, but neither defines what 'temperature' actually means. The Zeroth Law is the logical foundation on which the temperature concept rests. Renaming it as 'law 3' or '4' would disrupt the established numbering of the other laws, so it was inserted as '0' — prior to them in logical order."
