                answer: "Temperature is a measure of the average kinetic energy of molecules in a substance. When two objects at different temperatures are placed in contact, molecules at the interface collide. Faster (hotter) molecules transfer kinetic energy to slower (cooler) molecules during these collisions — a net flow of energy from the hotter to the cooler body. As the hotter body loses energy its molecules slow down; as the cooler body gains energy its molecules speed up. This continues until both bodies have the same average molecular kinetic energy — the same temperature. At this point, collisions at the interface transfer energy equally in both directions — for every collision that gives energy to the right, there is an equivalent one giving energy to the left. Net energy transfer becomes zero, and thermal equilibrium is established. Heat stops flowing not because collisions stop, but because energy exchange is symmetrical."
