                answer: "T_C = 278 K; T_H = 298 K. COP_Carnot = 278/(298 − 278) = 278/20 = 13.9. A perfect reversible refrigerator operating between these temperatures would extract 13.9 J of heat from the cold compartment for every 1 J of electrical work. The measured COP will be lower (typically 1–4 for real refrigerators) because real refrigerators have irreversibilities: friction in the compressor, heat transfer across finite temperature differences in the evaporator and condenser coils, throttling losses in the expansion valve, and electrical losses in the motor. All of these convert some of the work input into waste heat rather than useful cooling — reducing the fraction of work that contributes to heat extraction."
