                answer: "For a refrigerator used for cooling: COP_cooling = Q_C/W (heat extracted per unit work). For a heat pump used for heating: COP_HP = Q_H/W (heat rejected to the warm space per unit work). Since Q_H = Q_C + W (First Law energy balance): COP_HP = (Q_C + W)/W = Q_C/W + 1 = COP_cooling + 1. Therefore COP_HP is always exactly 1 greater than COP_cooling for the same device. For the example in Q1: COP_HP = 13.9 + 1 = 14.9 (Carnot maximum). This means the heat pump delivers up to 14.9 J of heat to the room for every 1 J of electrical work — making heat pumps far more efficient than direct electrical resistance heating (which always has COP = 1 by definition). This is why heat pumps are promoted as energy-efficient alternatives to gas boilers and resistance heaters."
