                hint: "Apply COP_Carnot = T_C/(T_H − T_C) for both temperatures. T_C must be in Kelvin.",
                answer: "Fridge (T_C = 5°C = 278 K, T_H = 298 K): COP_Carnot = 278/20 = 13.9. Freezer (T_C = −20°C = 253 K, T_H = 298 K): COP_Carnot = 253/45 = 5.62. Lowering T_C to −20°C reduces the Carnot COP from 13.9 to 5.62 — a reduction of more than half. Engineering implications: a freezer requires significantly more electrical energy per unit of heat extracted than a fridge at the same ambient temperature. The compressor must achieve higher compression ratios to reach −20°C evaporator temperatures, increasing mechanical stress and energy consumption. Freezers typically consume 30–60% more electricity than refrigerators of similar volume. This is why combined fridge-freezer units have separate compressors or carefully designed refrigerant flow paths to optimise COP for each compartment."
