                answer: "The criticism reflects a misunderstanding of COP. The First Law requires energy conservation across all energy flows, not just comparing Q_C to W. For COP = 3.2 with P_in = 100 W: Q_C = 3.2 × 100 = 320 W extracted from cold compartment; Q_H = Q_C + W = 320 + 100 = 420 W rejected to the room. Energy balance: energy in = W = 100 J/s (electrical). Energy out = Q_H = 420 J/s (to room). The extra 320 J/s came from the food — the refrigerator moved this energy from the food to the room using 100 J/s of electrical work to 'pump' it thermodynamically uphill (cold to hot). No energy was created; the total energy of food + electricity = total heat rejected to room (100 + 320 = 420 W). The COP > 1 does not violate the First Law — it simply measures how much heat is moved per unit of driving work, not how much energy is created."
