        introduction: "In 1787, the French physicist Jacques Charles observed that the volume of a fixed mass of gas at constant pressure decreases linearly with decreasing temperature, and in 1848 the British physicist William Thomson — later Lord Kelvin — used this linear relationship to define an absolute temperature scale, extrapolating the volume–temperature line to find the temperature at which gas volume would theoretically reach zero: absolute zero, at −273.15°C.",

        aim: "The aim of Charles's original investigation was to measure the relationship between gas volume and temperature at constant pressure, establishing the linear proportionality. Thomson's subsequent aim was to use this linear relationship to define a thermodynamic temperature scale independent of any particular material property — an absolute scale with a true zero grounded in physical law.",

        subject: "The subjects of Charles's experiments were sealed volumes of air and other gases in calibrated syringes or capillary tubes, heated and cooled in water baths of controlled temperature, with the gas column length (proportional to volume) measured at each temperature.",

        subjectDefinition: "The absolute temperature scale (Kelvin scale) is defined so that 0 K corresponds to absolute zero — the temperature at which an ideal gas would have zero volume (and zero kinetic energy), as extrapolated from the linear V–T relationship. The conversion is T(K) = T(°C) + 273.15. A gas thermometer uses the expansion of a gas at constant pressure (or the pressure change at constant volume) to measure temperature — it was historically the most accurate thermometer because gas behaviour is universal and predictable from kinetic theory. The extrapolation of the V vs T graph to V = 0 predicts absolute zero without ever reaching it experimentally.",

        results: "Charles found that for every 1°C rise in temperature, the volume of a gas at constant pressure increases by 1/273 of its volume at 0°C — a result that naturally suggests that volume would reach zero at −273°C. Thomson recognised that this temperature had physical significance as the lowest possible temperature and used it as the zero of an absolute temperature scale, naming the unit of absolute temperature the kelvin in later years. The modern value of absolute zero is −273.15°C (0 K).",

        modernConnection: "The absolute zero extrapolation experiment is a classic physics laboratory investigation that simultaneously verifies Charles's Law and calibrates the Kelvin temperature scale. The investigation below uses capillary tubes with trapped air columns in a water bath to measure gas column length versus temperature, plots V vs T in Celsius, and extrapolates the best-fit line to predict absolute zero — comparing the experimental extrapolation with the accepted value of −273.15°C.",

        contribution: "Charles established V ∝ T_absolute; Thomson defined the absolute temperature scale (Kelvin); extrapolation of gas volume to zero provides a practical determination of absolute zero",
