                answer: "Charles's Law states that gas volume is directly proportional to absolute temperature: V ∝ T_Kelvin. On a graph of V (or L) vs T in Celsius, this appears as a straight line — because T_Kelvin = T_Celsius + 273.15, which is a linear transformation. If the linear relationship continued to temperatures far below the experimental range, the line would eventually predict V = 0 at some temperature. The x-intercept gives this temperature: the temperature at which an ideal gas would have zero volume. This is the definition of absolute zero — the temperature of zero molecular kinetic energy and zero thermal pressure. We extrapolate mathematically because we cannot actually reach or measure absolute zero, and all real gases liquefy or solidify at temperatures far above 0 K — but the linear relationship, extrapolated, points precisely to the absolute temperature scale's origin."
