                answer: "Absolute zero (0 K = −273.15°C) represents the temperature at which molecules have minimum possible thermal energy. For an ideal gas, this corresponds to zero kinetic energy of translational motion — molecules would be completely stationary. For quantum mechanical systems, even at 0 K, particles retain a minimum 'zero-point energy' due to Heisenberg's uncertainty principle — so true rest is impossible even at 0 K. In practice, absolute zero can never be reached due to the Third Law of Thermodynamics, which states that it requires an infinite number of thermodynamic steps (infinite amounts of cooling work) to reduce the temperature of any system to exactly 0 K. Scientists have achieved temperatures of ~10⁻¹⁰ K (one ten-billionth of a kelvin) in specialised labs using laser cooling and adiabatic demagnetisation, but 0 K itself remains an asymptotic limit — always approachable, never reachable."
