        aim: "While Watt's practical aim was to maximise the commercial efficiency and power output of his steam engine, Carnot's theoretical aim was to determine the absolute maximum efficiency achievable by any heat engine operating between two temperature reservoirs, and to show that this limit was a universal thermodynamic law independent of the engine's mechanical design.",

        subject: "The subjects of Carnot's analysis — applied here to Watt's engine — were the hot steam boiler (acting as the hot reservoir at temperature T_H) and the condenser or atmosphere (acting as the cold reservoir at T_C), between which the engine converted heat to mechanical work. Watt's practical improvements — separate condenser, steam jacket, double-acting cylinder — all served to increase T_H and decrease T_C, pushing the engine closer to its Carnot limit.",

        subjectDefinition: "A steam engine is a heat engine that uses steam as its working fluid. High-pressure steam from the boiler (hot reservoir, T_H) expands in the cylinder, pushing the piston and doing mechanical work. The spent steam is condensed back to water in the condenser (cold reservoir, T_C). The Carnot efficiency η_Carnot = 1 − T_C/T_H represents the absolute upper limit of efficiency — no real steam engine can convert more of the heat from the boiler into work than this fraction, regardless of mechanical perfection. Real steam engines achieve 15–30% efficiency compared to Carnot limits of 50–70% at their operating temperatures.",

        results: "Carnot's theoretical analysis showed that Watt's steam engines, despite their impressive performance, were operating far below their theoretical efficiency limits. His framework predicted — before the First Law was even formally stated — that doubling the boiler temperature (in absolute terms) was more effective for improving efficiency than any mechanical refinement. This prediction guided 19th-century steam engineering: the development of high-pressure steam engines (higher T_H) and surface condensers (lower T_C) steadily improved real efficiency toward a higher fraction of the Carnot limit.",

        modernConnection: "The steam engine remains the dominant technology for electricity generation worldwide (coal, gas, and nuclear power stations all use steam turbines). The investigation below uses a model steam engine or a thermoelectric analog to measure work output and heat input at different boiler temperatures, calculating actual thermal efficiency and comparing it to the Carnot prediction at each operating temperature.",

