answer: "η_Carnot = 1 − 313/853 = 1 − 0.367 = 0.633 = 63.3%. Fraction of Carnot limit: 38/63.3 = 0.600 = 60%. The power station achieves 60% of its theoretical Carnot limit. This is excellent by engineering standards — modern supercritical steam power stations achieve 40–50% of Carnot, while the best gas turbine combined cycle plants reach 60–65% of their Carnot limit. The remaining 40% gap from Carnot in this example reflects irreversibilities: turbine blade friction, heat loss through boiler walls, non-ideal expansion, and losses in the cooling tower."
