                answer: "Let R_foam = 0.85R_total and R_ply + R_dry = 0.15R_total. Doubling plywood: New R_ply = 2R_ply_original. R_total_new = 2R_ply_original + R_foam + R_dry = R_total + R_ply_original. Since R_ply_original is small (part of only 15%), the increase in R_total is tiny — perhaps 3–5% increase at most. U decreases by the same small fraction. Doubling foam: New R_foam = 2 × 0.85R_total = 1.7R_total. New R_total = 1.7R_total + 0.15R_total = 1.85R_total. U_new = 1/(1.85R_total) ≈ 0.54/R_total ≈ 54% of original U — nearly half. This is the principle of dominant resistance: always improving the highest-resistance element gives the greatest return. In building design, improving window glazing (low resistance) while the walls are poorly insulated (high resistance) wastes money — the bottleneck must be addressed first."
