                answer: "A thermal bridge is a localised region in a building envelope where heat flows more readily than through the surrounding insulated wall — typically because a high-conductivity material (metal, concrete) spans the full wall thickness, bypassing the insulation layer. In the thermal resistance network, a thermal bridge creates a parallel low-resistance path alongside the high-resistance insulation — dramatically reducing the effective R-value of that section of the wall. Q_total = Q_insulation + Q_bridge; the bridge carries disproportionate heat flow. Real building example: steel-framed buildings have metal studs at regular intervals (typically every 600 mm) that extend from the inner to outer wall surface. Steel has k = 50 W/m·K, roughly 1250× higher than fibreglass insulation (k = 0.04). Even though studs occupy only ~10–15% of the wall area, they can reduce the effective wall R-value by 30–60% compared to the insulation-only calculation. Modern building practice uses thermal break materials (nylon or EPDM strips) between steel elements, or moves the insulation outside the structural frame (external insulation), to eliminate thermal bridges."
