        year: "1897",

        introduction: "In 1897, the German physicist Karl Ferdinand Braun invented the cathode ray tube oscilloscope at the University of Strasbourg, demonstrating that an electron beam could be deflected by electric and magnetic fields to trace voltage waveforms in real time on a phosphorescent screen — creating a device that made invisible electrical oscillations immediately and precisely visible for the first time.",

        aim: "The aim of Braun's invention was to provide physicists and engineers with a direct visual instrument for observing rapidly changing electrical signals — signals whose frequencies were far too high for any mechanical meter to follow — enabling the study of oscillating circuits, alternating currents, and electromagnetic waves that could not otherwise be directly observed.",

        subject: "The subject of Braun's oscilloscope development was the controlled deflection of a cathode ray (beam of electrons) by time-varying voltages applied to horizontal and vertical deflection plates — creating a two-dimensional trace on the screen that plotted a signal's voltage (y-axis) against time (x-axis), making the waveform, frequency, amplitude, and phase of any electrical signal directly readable.",

        subjectDefinition: "An oscilloscope is an electronic instrument that displays voltage signals as a waveform graph of voltage versus time. The y-axis represents voltage (amplitude of the signal) and the x-axis represents time. Key measurements from an oscilloscope: period T (time for one complete oscillation, read from peak-to-peak distance on the time axis); frequency f = 1/T; amplitude A (peak voltage, read from the midline to the crest); peak-to-peak voltage (2A). The oscilloscope's time base (seconds per division) determines the x-axis scale; the voltage sensitivity (volts per division) determines the y-axis scale.",

        results: "Braun's cathode ray tube oscilloscope proved transformative — it enabled direct measurement of alternating currents, radio frequency oscillations, and signal waveforms that no previous instrument could capture. Within decades, the oscilloscope became the most versatile and essential diagnostic instrument in all of electronics. Modern digital oscilloscopes (DSOs) achieve sampling rates of billions of samples per second and display frequencies into the gigahertz range, but the fundamental principle of plotting voltage versus time on a calibrated screen remains unchanged from Braun's 1897 invention.",

        modernConnection: "The oscilloscope is the fundamental instrument of electronics, telecommunications, acoustics, and physics teaching. The investigation below uses a signal generator and oscilloscope (or digital equivalent on a computer with a microphone) to display sine waves of different frequencies and amplitudes, measure period and peak voltage from the screen, verify f = 1/T, and compare waveforms from different sources (tuning fork, voice, electronic signal).",

        contribution: "Braun invented the cathode ray tube oscilloscope; demonstrated electron beam deflection for signal visualisation; created the first real-time waveform display instrument",
        significance: "The oscilloscope is the most essential electronic test instrument ever invented; enables design, testing, and troubleshooting of all electronic equipment; makes invisible electrical oscillations directly observable",
        quote: "The cathode ray tube has made visible for the first time the form of rapidly alternating currents — Karl Braun, 1909 Nobel Prize address"
