                hint: "Consider the definition of period and the independent nature of frequency and amplitude for a sine wave.",
                answer: "Period T and frequency f are reciprocals: f = 1/T, so T = 1/f. If frequency doubles (f → 2f), the period halves (T → T/2). On the oscilloscope, each complete cycle occupies T seconds of horizontal time — if T halves, the cycle occupies half as many horizontal divisions (or the same divisions but with the time base adjusted). Amplitude (V_peak) is the maximum displacement of the waveform from the midline — it is determined by the signal generator's output voltage level, which is set independently of frequency. Changing frequency does not change how high or low the wave travels — only how often. Therefore, doubling frequency: halves period (compressed cycles, more cycles per screen), but leaves amplitude unchanged (same height of peaks above midline). These two properties (frequency and amplitude) are completely independent parameters of a sine wave."
