                answer: "f_measured = 1/0.00227 ≈ 440.5 Hz. Percentage error = |440.5 − 440|/440 × 100% = 0.5/440 × 100% ≈ 0.11%. The agreement is excellent. Sources of error: (1) Division reading uncertainty: estimating the number of divisions per cycle to the nearest 0.1 division on the oscilloscope screen. If 4.4 divisions are read as 4.3 or 4.5, the calculated T changes by ≈2%, introducing significant frequency error. (2) Time base calibration: the actual time/div setting of the oscilloscope may differ from the nominal value by 1–3% due to calibration drift or temperature effects. (3) Microphone and amplifier frequency response: the microphone circuit may slightly delay or alter the signal, affecting the apparent period at the oscilloscope input. These three sources explain typical frequency measurement errors of 1–5% in student oscilloscope readings."
