        introduction: "Between 1760 and 1763, the Scottish physician and chemist Joseph Black conducted a series of careful calorimetric investigations at the University of Glasgow in which he compared the heating and cooling behaviour of different quantities and types of matter — distinguishing for the first time between the intensity of heat (temperature) and the quantity of heat (thermal energy) contained in a body.",

        aim: "The aim of his investigation was to determine whether temperature alone was a reliable measure of the heat content of a substance, and to establish that two objects at the same temperature could contain vastly different amounts of thermal energy depending on their mass and material.",

