        subjectDefinition: "Thermal energy (also called internal energy) is the total kinetic energy of all the particles in a substance — it depends on both the temperature and the amount (mass) of the substance. Temperature, by contrast, measures only the average kinetic energy per particle and is independent of quantity. A large cool body can therefore contain more thermal energy than a small hot body, even though its temperature is lower. This distinction is central to thermodynamics and heat transfer.",

        results: "Black found that when equal masses of water at different temperatures were mixed, the final equilibrium temperature was the arithmetic mean — demonstrating conservation of heat energy. More critically, he showed that a large mass of water at a moderate temperature could melt far more ice than a small mass at a high temperature, proving that temperature alone does not predict the heating effect. He coined the term 'latent heat' for energy absorbed without temperature change, and distinguished 'heat capacity' as the energy needed to change a body's temperature by one degree.",

        modernConnection: "Black's distinction between thermal energy and temperature is the conceptual foundation of calorimetry and thermodynamics. The investigation below makes this contrast vivid and concrete: students compare a large volume of warm water (bathtub scale) with a small volume of hot water (cup scale) and reason about which contains more thermal energy, directly replicating Black's core insight that temperature ≠ heat content.",

