                hint: "Calculate Q = mcΔT for each, then compare totals. Think about which has more energy to give away.",
                answer: "Bathtub: Q = 200 × 4200 × (35 − 20) = 200 × 4200 × 15 = 12,600,000 J = 12.6 MJ. Cup: Q = 0.25 × 4200 × (90 − 20) = 0.25 × 4200 × 70 = 73,500 J = 73.5 kJ. The bathtub contains approximately 171 times more thermal energy than the cup. Despite the cup having a much higher temperature, the bathtub's enormous mass gives it vastly more heat to transfer. For heating a room, the bathtub would be far more effective — it can continue releasing heat as it slowly cools from 35°C toward room temperature, whereas the cup would be exhausted almost immediately. This demonstrates Joseph Black's insight: thermal energy is a function of both temperature and mass."
