                answer: "Using conservation of energy: heat lost by hot water = heat gained by cold water. m₁c(T₁ − T_f) = m₂c(T_f − T₂). Since c cancels: 0.400 × (60 − T_f) = 0.200 × (T_f − 15). Expanding: 24 − 0.4T_f = 0.2T_f − 3. Rearranging: 24 + 3 = 0.2T_f + 0.4T_f. 27 = 0.6T_f. T_f = 27/0.6 = 45°C. The final equilibrium temperature is 45°C. Note that it is closer to the temperature of the larger mass (60°C) than to the smaller mass (15°C) — the larger mass dominates the final temperature because it carries more thermal energy."
