                answer: "A critical example is steam burns versus boiling water burns. Steam at 100°C and boiling water at 100°C are at the same temperature, but steam releases an additional 2,260,000 J/kg of latent heat as it condenses onto skin, before it even begins to cool. This means steam causes far more severe burns than boiling water at the same temperature because it carries vastly more thermal energy per kilogram. A cook who treats steam as 'just 100°C water' may underestimate the burn hazard. Another example: in cooking, a metal tray and a piece of bread at the same oven temperature feel very different when touched — the metal has higher thermal conductivity and transfers heat faster, but also has different heat capacity, so the amount of energy it delivers per contact is different despite identical temperature."
