        introduction: "Between 1760 and 1764, the Scottish chemist Joseph Black conducted systematic heating experiments at the University of Glasgow in which he heated equal masses of different substances — water, mercury, iron, and other metals — with the same source of heat for the same duration, and discovered that they reached dramatically different final temperatures.",

        aim: "The aim of his investigation was to determine why different substances require different amounts of heat to change their temperature by the same amount — establishing that the quantity of heat needed per degree of temperature rise per unit mass is a fixed characteristic property of each material.",

        subject: "The subjects of Black's experiments were equal masses of water, mercury, iron, and various metals, heated by identical heat sources for identical durations, with temperature rises measured using calibrated thermometers.",

        subjectDefinition: "Specific heat capacity (c) is the amount of thermal energy required to raise the temperature of one kilogram of a substance by one degree Celsius (or one Kelvin). It is measured in joules per kilogram per degree Celsius (J/kg°C). A substance with a high specific heat capacity (like water, c = 4200 J/kg°C) requires a lot of energy to heat up and cools down slowly. A substance with a low specific heat capacity (like copper, c = 385 J/kg°C) heats up quickly with little energy. The equation relating thermal energy, mass, specific heat capacity, and temperature change is Q = mcΔT.",

        results: "Black found that water required approximately ten times more heat than mercury to produce the same temperature rise in equal masses. He concluded that each substance has a characteristic 'capacity for heat' — now called specific heat capacity. He demonstrated that this property was constant for a given material over a reasonable temperature range, and that it explained the thermal inertia of large water bodies like lakes and oceans. Black never quantified c in modern units, but his qualitative discovery enabled all subsequent quantitative calorimetry.",

        modernConnection: "Black's discovery of specific heat capacity is the direct basis of the equation Q = mcΔT, which underpins all calorimetry. The investigation below uses an electrical immersion heater to deliver a known quantity of heat energy (Q = PΔt = VIΔt) to metal blocks of aluminium and copper, and to water — allowing students to calculate c for each material and compare to accepted values, directly replicating Black's comparative heating experiments with modern electrical precision.",

        contribution: "Discovered that different substances have different heat capacities per unit mass; established the concept of specific heat capacity; introduced the thermal inertia of materials",
        significance: "Foundation of calorimetry, thermodynamics, and materials science; explains why water is used as a coolant and thermal store",
