                answer: "Energy supplied: Q = PΔt = 30 × (5 × 60) = 30 × 300 = 9000 J. Expected temperature rise: ΔT = Q/(mc) = 9000/(0.500 × 900) = 9000/450 = 20°C. In practice, the actual temperature rise is smaller because not all 9000 J goes into the aluminium block — some is lost to the surroundings through the insulating jacket (conduction and radiation), some heats the thermometer and immersion heater themselves, and some is radiated directly from the heater. These heat losses mean less energy enters the block per second than the full 30 W, so ΔT_actual < 20°C. This is why measured c values appear higher than accepted values: c = Q/(mΔT_measured), and if ΔT_measured is smaller than expected, c appears larger."
