                answer: "Water has a specific heat capacity of approximately 4200 J/kg°C — the highest of any common liquid. Mercury has c ≈ 140 J/kg°C — about 30 times less. This means that for every kilogram of coolant used, water can absorb 30 times more thermal energy before its temperature rises by 1°C. A car engine generates thousands of joules of waste heat per second. Using water, this heat is spread across a large thermal capacity and transported to the radiator with only a modest temperature rise. If mercury were used, it would heat up 30 times faster, potentially reaching dangerous temperatures quickly. Water's high specific heat capacity makes it an exceptionally efficient thermal buffer — it absorbs large amounts of heat energy for small temperature rises, keeping the engine within safe operating temperature."
