                hint: "Think about what holds ice particles together compared to liquid water, and what melting requires.",
                answer: "In the solid ice lattice, water molecules are held in fixed positions by strong hydrogen bonds arranged in a crystalline structure. During melting, the supplied thermal energy is used to break these hydrogen bonds rather than increasing the speed of the molecules. Breaking bonds requires energy but does not increase kinetic energy — and it is average kinetic energy that determines temperature. So while energy is being absorbed, none of it goes into particle motion; instead it all goes into overcoming intermolecular attractive forces and releasing molecules from the crystal lattice into the disordered liquid state. Only once all bonds holding the crystal together are broken (all ice melted) can additional energy go into increasing particle speed — at which point temperature begins to rise again. This is why temperature stays fixed at 0°C throughout melting."
