                answer: "The slope of the temperature–time graph is ΔT/Δt = P/(mc). For constant P and constant m, slope is inversely proportional to c: slope ∝ 1/c. For ice: slope_ice ∝ 1/2100. For water: slope_water ∝ 1/4200. Ratio: slope_ice / slope_water = 4200/2100 = 2. The ice heats up twice as fast as the liquid water for the same heater power — its temperature–time slope is twice as steep. This can be observed directly on the heating curve: the gradient before the plateau (solid ice region) is approximately twice as steep as the gradient after the plateau (liquid water region). Measuring this ratio provides an indirect way to estimate the ratio of specific heat capacities of ice and water."
