                answer: "On clear nights, the ground loses heat rapidly by infrared radiation to the cold sky — there are no clouds to reflect this radiation back. As the ground cools, air near the surface can drop below 0°C, causing frost. On cloudy nights, clouds absorb outgoing infrared radiation and re-emit some back toward the ground, reducing the net heat loss — acting like a thermal blanket. Additionally, latent heat of fusion plays a critical role as temperatures approach 0°C: if moisture on grass, soil, or plants begins to freeze, it releases latent heat (L_f = 334,000 J/kg) back into the surroundings. This released energy temporarily moderates the local temperature, slowing the cooling process. In practice, this means the temperature near the ground stays close to 0°C for longer as water freezes, and frost formation is delayed — particularly in humid conditions where more water is available to freeze and release latent heat."
