                question: "The latent heat of vaporisation of water is L_v = 2,260,000 J/kg — approximately 6.8 times greater than L_f = 334,000 J/kg. Explain at the molecular level why so much more energy is needed to vaporise water than to melt it.",
                hint: "Compare what happens to intermolecular distances and bonds during melting versus vaporisation.",
                answer: "During melting (solid → liquid), ice crystal bonds are partially broken — molecules gain enough energy to move past each other in the liquid state, but they remain in close contact and retain significant intermolecular attractions. The average intermolecular distance increases only slightly, and molecules are still strongly interacting in the liquid. During vaporisation (liquid → gas), molecules must be completely separated from all neighbours and moved to distances where intermolecular forces are negligible. This requires overcoming all remaining hydrogen bonds and van der Waals attractions over a much larger distance than melting requires. Furthermore, the gas must do work expanding against atmospheric pressure (PΔV work) as it occupies a volume approximately 1700 times greater than the liquid. Both the complete bond-breaking energy and the expansion work contribute to the much larger value of L_v compared to L_f."
