                answer: "The thermostat switches ON at 18°C and switches OFF at 22°C. The hysteresis is 4°C (22 − 18 = 4°C). Hysteresis is desirable because it prevents 'chattering' — rapid switching on and off when the temperature hovers very close to a single threshold. If the thermostat switched at exactly, say, 20°C for both on and off, a tiny fluctuation of ±0.1°C could cause it to switch on and off many times per minute. Repeated rapid switching damages the relay contacts and the heater motor through thermal and electrical stress. The 4°C hysteresis ensures the heater runs for a useful period before switching off, and cools for a useful period before switching back on — providing a stable, economical heating cycle. The temperature oscillates in a controlled band (18–22°C) rather than at a single point."
