                hint: "The curvature arises from the difference in expansion — what if the difference is zero?",
                answer: "If both metals have identical coefficients of thermal expansion (α₁ = α₂), then for any temperature change ΔT, both metals expand by exactly the same amount: ΔL₁ = α₁ × L₀ × ΔT = ΔL₂ = α₂ × L₀ × ΔT. Since there is no length mismatch between the two layers, there is no differential expansion and no force causing the strip to curve. The bonded strip expands uniformly in length, just as a single-metal rod would — it remains straight at all temperatures. This confirms that the bimetallic effect requires a difference in α between the two bonded metals: the larger the difference, the greater the deflection per degree. This is why bimetallic strips are designed to maximise the contrast between the two metals — for example, using invar (α ≈ 1 × 10⁻⁶ °C⁻¹, very low expansion) paired with brass (α ≈ 19 × 10⁻⁶ °C⁻¹, high expansion) to maximise the differential and therefore the deflection sensitivity."
