                answer: "The vacuum gap eliminates conduction and convection — both require a material medium for heat transfer. Conduction needs particles in contact to pass vibrations along; convection requires a fluid (gas or liquid) to carry heat by bulk movement. A vacuum contains neither, so both modes are completely eliminated by the vacuum gap. The silvered walls minimise radiation — highly polished silver surfaces have very low emissivity (ε ≈ 0.02) and very low absorptivity. The inner silvered wall reflects infrared radiation from the hot liquid back inward rather than absorbing it, while the outer silvered wall reflects room-temperature radiation from the environment back outward rather than absorbing it. The thin plastic stopper minimises conduction at the neck — plastic has a low thermal conductivity (k ≈ 0.1–0.5 W/m·K compared to metal at 50–400 W/m·K), and its small cross-sectional area further limits conduction. Together, all three features address all three heat transfer modes, keeping hot drinks hot and cold drinks cold for hours."
