                hint: "Fourier's law: Q/t = kAΔT/d. For the same A, ΔT, and d, the ratio of conduction rates equals the ratio of k values.",
                answer: "By Fourier's law: (Q/t) = kAΔT/d. For the same rod dimensions (same A and d) and the same temperature difference (same ΔT), the heat flow rate is directly proportional to k. Ratio of conduction rates: (Q/t)_Cu / (Q/t)_glass = k_Cu / k_glass = 400 / 1.0 = 400. Copper conducts heat 400 times faster than glass under the same conditions. This explains the dramatic difference observed in the wax-melting experiment: in the same time that copper transmits heat the full length of the rod, glass barely transmits heat at all. This is why copper and aluminium are used for cooking pans (rapid, even heat distribution) while glass and ceramic are used for oven dishes where gradual, even heating is preferred and insulating handles prevent burns."
