        introduction: "Between 1793 and 1820, the English meteorologist Luke Howard and the chemist John Dalton made careful comparative temperature records in English cities and coastal towns, observing that coastal locations experienced far smaller daily and seasonal temperature swings than inland locations at similar latitudes — and attributed this difference to the moderating influence of the ocean.",

        aim: "The aim of their meteorological investigations was to identify systematic differences in temperature variation between coastal and inland locations, and to propose a physical mechanism — the thermal buffering capacity of the ocean — that explained why maritime climates are more temperate than continental climates.",

        subject: "The subjects of their investigations were long-term temperature records from coastal cities (e.g. London, Bristol, Dublin) compared to inland continental cities at similar latitudes (e.g. Moscow, Warsaw), with daily and annual temperature ranges compared statistically.",

        subjectDefinition: "Specific heat capacity (c) is the energy required to change the temperature of 1 kg of a substance by 1°C. Water has an exceptionally high specific heat capacity of approximately 4200 J/kg°C — roughly four times that of rock (≈ 800 J/kg°C) and ten times that of iron. This means that for the same amount of solar energy absorbed, water heats up far less than land. Conversely, when evening or winter cooling occurs, water releases far more energy per degree of temperature drop than land does — acting as a thermal buffer. Coastal regions experience moderated temperature extremes because the adjacent ocean absorbs solar energy without greatly increasing in temperature during the day or summer, and slowly releases it during night or winter.",

        results: "Howard and Dalton found that coastal cities had annual temperature ranges of 10–15°C, while continental cities at the same latitude had ranges of 30–40°C. Daily temperature ranges at the coast were typically 5–8°C compared to 15–25°C inland. These differences were consistent with the heat capacity contrast between water (slow to heat and cool) and rock/soil (fast to heat and cool). The pattern was confirmed across all maritime climates globally and linked quantitatively to c_water >> c_land.",

        modernConnection: "Water's anomalously high specific heat capacity is a foundational concept in both chemistry and Earth science. The investigation below replicates the coastal vs inland climate contrast in a laboratory model: equal masses of water and sand are heated by the same lamp for the same time, and their different temperature rises demonstrate why coastal (water-adjacent) regions have smaller temperature swings than inland (land-dominated) regions.",

