                answer: "The rapid cooling of sand (low c) versus slow cooling of water (high c) models the sea breeze cycle observed on coastlines. During the day, land (sand, soil, rock) heats up rapidly in the sun and becomes much hotter than the adjacent sea. Hot air over the land rises (convection), and cooler air from over the sea flows in as a sea breeze — a refreshing onshore wind. At night, the land cools rapidly while the sea retains its warmth. Air over the warmer sea rises, and the now-cooler land air flows out to sea as a land breeze. This daily cycle is practically significant in several ways: it moderates coastal temperatures (making beach towns more liveable in summer), it drives fishing boat operations (traditional fishermen used land breezes to go to sea at night and sea breezes to return in the morning), and it determines smoke dispersal patterns from coastal industrial sites, affecting air quality planning."
