                question: "Global warming involves the ocean absorbing approximately 90% of the excess heat trapped by greenhouse gases. Using the concept of specific heat capacity, explain why this has temporarily moderated atmospheric temperature rises, and what concern this raises about the long-term heat content of the ocean.",
                hint: "Think about where excess heat is going (ocean vs atmosphere) and what happens to Q = mcΔT when c and m are very large.",
                answer: "The ocean has an enormous thermal mass: m_ocean ≈ 1.4 × 10²¹ kg and c_water = 4200 J/kg°C. Because Q = mcΔT, for a given absorbed energy Q, ΔT = Q/(mc). With such a massive m and high c, the ocean's temperature rise for absorbing 90% of excess trapped heat is very small — approximately 0.1°C per decade at the surface and much less in deeper layers. This explains why global average air temperatures have risen more slowly than they would if the atmosphere absorbed all excess heat (c_air is very low and m_air is far smaller per unit area). However, this moderation is temporary and raises serious concerns: the ocean is accumulating vast amounts of thermal energy (ocean heat content is now a primary measure of global warming). When ocean surface temperatures rise sufficiently, they drive more intense hurricanes (which draw energy from warm surface water), accelerate melting of ice sheets through warm water contact, and reduce the ocean's capacity to absorb further CO₂ (warm water holds less dissolved gas). The stored thermal energy also commits the climate to continued warming even if greenhouse gas emissions were stopped today."
