                answer: "Temperature must be in Kelvin because gas laws are based on absolute temperature — the Kelvin scale starts at absolute zero (−273.15°C), the point at which molecular motion theoretically ceases and gas volume extrapolates to zero. The gas laws state V ∝ T, meaning volume is zero at T = 0 K. If Celsius is used, T = 0°C (273.15 K) is not zero volume — so the proportionality V/T = constant does not hold in Celsius. As a mathematical example: if gas at 0°C is heated to 100°C at constant pressure. Using Kelvin: V₂/V₁ = T₂/T₁ = 373/273 = 1.37 — volume increases by 37%. Using Celsius: V₂/V₁ = 100/0 = undefined (division by zero). Even if 0°C is avoided, using 20°C and 40°C: Kelvin gives 313/293 = 1.07 (correct 7% increase); Celsius gives 40/20 = 2.0 (incorrect 100% increase). The Celsius calculation is completely wrong. Always convert to Kelvin: T(K) = T(°C) + 273.15."
