                answer: "In Boyle's J-tube, one end is sealed (trapping air) and the other is open to the atmosphere. Mercury fills the curved bottom and rises in both arms. The pressure on the trapped gas equals atmospheric pressure plus the pressure from any extra mercury in the open arm above the level of mercury in the sealed arm. The pressure from a column of mercury is P_mercury = ρ_Hg × g × h, where ρ_Hg = 13,600 kg/m³, g = 9.81 m/s², and h is the height difference between mercury levels in the two arms. For example, if the open arm has mercury 76 cm higher than the closed arm: P_mercury = 13,600 × 9.81 × 0.76 ≈ 101,325 Pa = 1 atm. So adding 76 cm of mercury doubles the pressure from atmospheric to 2 atm. Boyle used this to precisely control and calculate pressure on the trapped air — a remarkably accurate method for the 17th century."
