                answer: "An extensive property depends on the amount (quantity) of matter — it doubles if the amount of substance doubles. An intensive property is independent of the amount of matter. Temperature (T) is intensive: the temperature of a gas does not change if you double the amount of gas at the same conditions — each molecule still has the same average kinetic energy. Pressure (P) is also intensive: pressure is force per unit area, which does not depend on how much gas there is (as long as the container adjusts accordingly). Volume (V) is extensive: if you double the amount of gas at constant T and P, the volume doubles — V ∝ n (Avogadro's Law). In the ideal gas law PV = nRT: T and P are intensive, V and n are extensive. This distinction matters because intensive variables describe the state of each individual particle, while extensive variables describe the bulk quantity of the gas sample."
