                answer: "The combined gas law is: P₁V₁/T₁ = P₂V₂/T₂ = constant (for fixed n). This is the general relationship for a fixed mass of ideal gas. The three individual laws are special cases: (1) Boyle's Law: hold T constant (T₁ = T₂). The equation becomes P₁V₁ = P₂V₂ — pressure and volume are inversely proportional. (2) Charles's Law: hold P constant (P₁ = P₂). The equation becomes V₁/T₁ = V₂/T₂ — volume is directly proportional to absolute temperature. (3) Gay-Lussac's Law: hold V constant (V₁ = V₂). The equation becomes P₁/T₁ = P₂/T₂ — pressure is directly proportional to absolute temperature. The combined gas law unifies all three into a single equation by allowing all three variables to change simultaneously, with the constraint that PV/T remains constant for a fixed amount of ideal gas."
