                answer: "Gay-Lussac's Law (P ∝ T at constant V) requires a rigid container because if the container is flexible, the volume adjusts to maintain constant pressure rather than allowing pressure to rise. In a balloon, when temperature increases, the balloon expands (V increases) to accommodate the increasing molecular energy while keeping the internal pressure close to atmospheric — this is Charles's Law (V ∝ T at constant P), not Gay-Lussac's Law. The choice of constraint (constant V or constant P) determines which law operates: rigid container → Gay-Lussac; flexible container at atmospheric pressure → Charles. In a rigid sealed container, volume cannot change, so all the effect of increased temperature appears as increased pressure — Gay-Lussac's Law. If the container is flexible but has a non-zero elastic restoring force (like a thick rubber balloon), the situation is intermediate — both P and V change with temperature."
