                answer: "Both laws extrapolate to the same absolute zero because both arise from the same underlying physical principle: the average kinetic energy of gas molecules is proportional to T(K) — E_k = (3/2)kT. At T = 0 K, E_k = 0 — no molecular motion. For Charles's Law (constant P): V = (nR/P) × T → V = 0 at T = 0 K. For Gay-Lussac's Law (constant V): P = (nR/V) × T → P = 0 at T = 0 K. Both equations are linear functions of T(K) passing through the origin. When plotted against T(°C), both extrapolate to zero at T = −273.15°C because 0 K = −273.15°C. The convergence of both laws to the same intercept is not a coincidence — it reflects that pressure, volume, and temperature are all connected through the same fundamental equation (ideal gas law PV = nRT), and that T = 0 K is the universal physical zero for all thermal phenomena."
