                answer: "Two competing effects occur during ascent. Gay-Lussac's Law effect: temperature decreases with altitude (the troposphere cools at approximately −6.5°C/km). Lower temperature means lower average molecular kinetic energy and therefore lower pressure at constant volume — Gay-Lussac's Law predicts decreasing internal pressure. Boyle's Law effect: atmospheric pressure decreases with altitude (from ~101 kPa at sea level to ~41 kPa at 7 km). The balloon's envelope responds to the lower external pressure by expanding (Charles/Boyle behaviour) — internal pressure adjusts toward atmospheric. The net result depends on whether the balloon is sealed or has a pressure-relief valve. In Gay-Lussac's open-neck hydrogen balloon, internal pressure stayed approximately equal to external atmospheric pressure (the neck allowed gas to escape as the balloon expanded). The volume of the balloon increased as external pressure decreased (Boyle effect), while the temperature decrease worked to partially counteract this expansion. The observed dramatic increase in balloon volume at altitude is primarily the Boyle's Law effect of decreasing external pressure, partially offset by the Charles/Gay-Lussac contraction from lower temperature."
