                answer: "From PV = nRT: P = nRT/V. If n decreases (gas leaks out) while V and T are fixed, P decreases. A slow leak during the experiment means n is gradually decreasing throughout. At low temperatures (measured first), n is still close to its original value, so P is close to the ideal value. At higher temperatures (measured later), more gas has leaked out, so n is noticeably lower, and P is lower than Gay-Lussac's Law predicts for that temperature. The P/T ratios would therefore decrease with temperature — the data points would fall below the expected straight line at higher temperatures, and the apparent gradient of the P vs T(K) graph would be shallower than the true value. The deviation would be systematic (progressively worsening, not random), which is a diagnostic sign of a leak. The student could verify this by checking whether the room-temperature pressure reading after the experiment is lower than at the start — a drop would confirm gas loss."
