        introduction: "In 1811, the Italian physicist and chemist Amedeo Avogadro published a landmark paper in the Journal de Physique proposing that equal volumes of different gases at the same temperature and pressure contain the same number of molecules — directly contradicting the prevailing belief (due to John Dalton) that different gases had different atomic sizes and that combining volumes of gases in chemical reactions required a complex correction scheme.",

        aim: "The aim of Avogadro's theoretical and experimental investigation was to reconcile Gay-Lussac's experimental law of combining gas volumes with Dalton's atomic theory — proposing a unifying hypothesis (now law) that would explain why gases always combine in simple whole-number volume ratios in chemical reactions.",

        subject: "The subjects of Avogadro's analysis were the combining volume ratios of gases in chemical reactions: hydrogen + oxygen → water (2:1:2 volumes), nitrogen + hydrogen → ammonia (1:3:2 volumes), and others — which could only be explained if equal volumes contained equal numbers of molecules regardless of gas type.",

        subjectDefinition: "Avogadro's Law states that at constant temperature and pressure, the volume of an ideal gas is directly proportional to the number of moles of gas: V ∝ n, or V₁/n₁ = V₂/n₂. The proportionality constant at standard temperature and pressure (0°C, 101.325 kPa) gives a molar volume of 22.4 L/mol — meaning one mole of any ideal gas occupies 22.4 litres at STP. At room conditions (25°C, 101.325 kPa), the molar volume is approximately 24.5 L/mol. This law completes the ideal gas law: combined with Boyle's and Charles's Laws, it gives PV = nRT.",

        results: "Avogadro showed that by assuming equal volumes contain equal numbers of molecules (at same T and P), the combining volume ratios of all known gas reactions were correctly predicted. His hypothesis was largely ignored for 50 years until Stanislao Cannizzaro revived it at the 1860 Karlsruhe Congress, where it was finally accepted and used to establish consistent atomic weights. Avogadro's number (6.022 × 10²³ molecules/mol) was named in his honour by Jean Perrin in 1909.",

        modernConnection: "Avogadro's Law — that volume is proportional to moles at constant T and P — can be demonstrated directly by comparing volumes of different amounts of gas in identical conditions. The investigation below uses inflated balloons containing measured masses of different gases or different numbers of moles of the same gas, compares their volumes at the same T and P, and verifies V ∝ n — connecting Avogadro's abstract molecular hypothesis to a measurable, tangible proportionality.",

