answer: "Gay-Lussac observed: 2 volumes of hydrogen + 1 volume of oxygen → 2 volumes of steam (water vapour). By Avogadro's Law, equal volumes at same T and P contain equal numbers of molecules. So: 2 molecules of hydrogen + 1 molecule of oxygen → 2 molecules of water. This requires each water molecule to contain atoms from both gases. The product (2 water molecules) contains all the atoms from 2 hydrogen molecules + 1 oxygen molecule. If hydrogen is H₂ and oxygen is O₂ (Avogadro assumed diatomic molecules): 2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O. Checking: left side: 4 H atoms + 2 O atoms. Right side: 2 × (2H + 1O) = 4 H + 2 O. Balanced — each water molecule contains 2 hydrogen atoms and 1 oxygen atom, giving the formula H₂O. This derivation was only possible because Avogadro correctly assumed diatomic hydrogen and oxygen molecules — without this assumption, the combining volumes cannot be reconciled with a consistent formula."
