                answer: "In kinetic molecular theory, gas pressure arises from the rate of molecular collisions with container walls — each collision imparts a tiny impulse, and summed over many collisions per unit area per second, this gives macroscopic pressure. The pressure from one type of molecule (say, oxygen) depends only on the number density of oxygen molecules, their mass, and their average speed — all determined by temperature. Whether nitrogen molecules are also present in the container is irrelevant: oxygen molecules collide with walls at the same rate and with the same force regardless of nitrogen's presence, because ideal gas molecules do not interact with each other (no intermolecular forces between unlike molecules). Each gas species therefore generates its own independent partial pressure. The total pressure is simply the total rate of collisions from all molecular species: P_total = P_O₂ + P_N₂ + P_Ar + ... This is Dalton's Law — a direct consequence of the non-interacting ideal gas molecule assumption."
