                answer: "Initial total pressure: P_total = P_O₂ + P_N₂ + P_water = 40 + 60 + 5 = 105 kPa. When water vapour condenses completely: P_water drops to effectively 0 kPa (all vapour has become liquid). The partial pressures of O₂ and N₂ remain unchanged (Dalton's Law — each gas behaves independently). New total pressure: P_total_new = 40 + 60 + 0 = 100 kPa. In practice, P_water does not drop to exactly 0 but to the saturation vapour pressure at the new (lower) temperature. If the new temperature is well below the dew point, P_water is negligible. The 5 kPa reduction corresponds exactly to the removal of the water vapour component — Dalton's Law makes this calculation straightforward."
