                hint: "P_i = x_i × P_total where x_i is mole fraction. Water vapour P is fixed by the saturation vapour pressure at 37°C.",
                answer: "Using Dalton's Law (P_i = mole fraction × P_total for ideal gases): P(O₂) = 0.135 × 101 = 13.6 kPa; P(CO₂) = 0.053 × 101 = 5.4 kPa; P(H₂O) = 0.062 × 101 = 6.3 kPa; P(N₂) = (1 − 0.135 − 0.053 − 0.062) × 101 = 0.750 × 101 = 75.8 kPa. P_H₂O in the lungs is always approximately 6.27 kPa because the alveolar air is in equilibrium with the moist lung surface — the air is fully saturated with water vapour at body temperature (37°C). The saturation vapour pressure of water at 37°C is fixed by thermodynamics at 6.27 kPa, regardless of the other gases present (Dalton's Law). This is why divers and high-altitude aviators must account for this fixed water vapour pressure when calculating available O₂ partial pressure from total breathing gas pressure."
