                hint: "Natural breathing uses negative pressure (pull); mechanical ventilation uses positive pressure (push). Think about what happens to pressure distribution in the lungs.",
                answer: "Natural breathing (negative pressure): the diaphragm and intercostal muscles expand the chest, reducing intra-pleural pressure. Air flows in passively due to the pressure gradient (P_atm > P_lung). Pressures throughout the lung are sub-atmospheric, and the expansion is gentle and even because the whole thorax expands simultaneously. Mechanical ventilation (positive pressure): the ventilator pushes air into the airways under positive pressure (P_vent > P_atm). Air is forced into the lungs, compressing the alveoli and increasing intra-alveolar pressure above atmospheric. The mechanics are opposite to natural breathing — pressure is applied from the airway side rather than the pleural side. A key risk of positive-pressure ventilation is barotrauma (pressure injury): if the delivered pressure is too high, it can rupture alveolar walls, causing pneumothorax (air leaks into the pleural space) or subcutaneous emphysema (air tracking under the skin). Additionally, high positive pressure can reduce venous return to the heart (by compressing thoracic veins), decreasing cardiac output — a phenomenon called ventilator-induced hemodynamic compromise."
