                answer: "T = 37°C = 310 K (body temperature — the gas is warmed in the airways). Moles of air per breath at altitude: n = PV/RT = (50,000 × 500 × 10⁻⁶) / (8.314 × 310) = 25 / 2577.3 = 9.70 × 10⁻³ mol. Moles of O₂ per breath: n(O₂) = 0.21 × 9.70 × 10⁻³ = 2.04 × 10⁻³ mol. Mass of O₂ per breath: 2.04 × 10⁻³ × 32 = 0.0652 g. Mass per minute at 20 breaths: 0.0652 × 20 = 1.30 g/min. At sea level: n = (101,000 × 500 × 10⁻⁶)/(8.314 × 310) = 50.5/2577.3 = 1.96 × 10⁻² mol. n(O₂) per breath = 0.21 × 1.96 × 10⁻² = 4.12 × 10⁻³ mol. Mass per breath = 0.132 g. Mass per minute = 0.132 × 20 = 2.64 g/min. At altitude, the climber inhales only 1.30/2.64 = 49% as much O₂ per minute as at sea level — despite the same breathing rate and tidal volume. To compensate, high-altitude acclimatisation increases both respiratory rate and tidal volume (hyperventilation), and the body produces more red blood cells."
