                hint: "Consider one molecule bouncing between two walls separated by length L. Calculate the force from one molecule, then sum over all N molecules.",
                answer: "Consider N molecules in a cubic box of side L (volume V = L³). For one molecule moving with x-velocity v_x: (1) It hits one wall, and elastic collision reverses its x-momentum: Δp = 2mv_x. (2) Time to return to same wall (travel 2L): Δt = 2L/v_x. (3) Force from one molecule on one wall: F₁ = Δp/Δt = 2mv_x / (2L/v_x) = mv_x²/L. (4) Total force from all N molecules on one wall: F = Σᵢ mv_xi²/L = (Nm/L)⟨v_x²⟩. (5) By symmetry, ⟨v_x²⟩ = ⟨v_y²⟩ = ⟨v_z²⟩ = (1/3)⟨v²⟩. (6) Pressure = F/A = F/L² = (Nm/L³)⟨v_x²⟩ = (N/V)m(1/3)⟨v²⟩ = (1/3)(N/V)m⟨v²⟩. Since N/V = number density and m = molecular mass, P = (1/3)ρ⟨v²⟩. From this, PV = (1/3)Nm⟨v²⟩ = (2/3)N × (½m⟨v²⟩) = (2/3)N × E_k_per_molecule. Comparing to PV = nRT = Nk_BT, we get E_k_per_molecule = (3/2)k_BT — the kinetic energy-temperature relationship."
