                answer: "In the model, doubling N doubles the force (and pressure) at constant shaking speed and box size. This directly demonstrates that P ∝ N (at constant V and T) — when you add more molecules to a fixed-volume container, pressure increases proportionally. This is the microscopic basis of Gay-Lussac's Law for adding molecules, or equivalently, it is the converse of Avogadro's Law. Avogadro's Law states V ∝ n at constant P and T — if you keep pressure constant but add more molecules, the volume must increase proportionally to maintain P = (1/3)(N/V)m⟨v²⟩ constant. To connect: if N doubles, PV = Nm⟨v²⟩/3 doubles. To keep P constant, V must double. So adding more molecules to a flexible container (constant P) doubles its volume — Avogadro's Law. In a rigid box (constant V), adding more molecules doubles the pressure — Gay-Lussac variant. Boyle's Law relates to changing V while keeping N and T constant, which would correspond to compressing the box with the same number of balls."
