                answer: "The Maxwell-Boltzmann speed distribution describes the fraction of molecules with each speed in an ideal gas at temperature T. It is: (1) Zero at v = 0 (no molecules are completely stationary). (2) Rises steeply to a peak at the most probable speed v_p = √(2RT/M). (3) Then falls gradually with a long tail toward high speeds — the distribution is positively skewed. The three characteristic speeds are, in order: v_p (most probable) < v_mean (mean) < v_rms (root mean square). For nitrogen at 300 K: v_p ≈ 422 m/s, v_mean ≈ 476 m/s, v_rms ≈ 517 m/s. The tail toward high speeds is important because it is the high-speed molecules that: (a) escape from liquid surfaces (evaporation); (b) cross activation energy barriers in chemical reactions (Arrhenius temperature dependence); (c) enable effusion through tiny orifices (Graham's Law). A uniform-speed ping-pong ball model cannot reproduce this tail and therefore underestimates the fraction of high-energy collisions."
