                answer: "From P = (1/3)(N/V)m⟨v²⟩, define the constant k_gas = (1/3)Nm⟨v²⟩ (which depends only on N, m, and temperature T). Then: Boyle's Law: if temperature is constant (T = constant), then ⟨v²⟩ = constant (since E_k = ½m⟨v²⟩ ∝ T). Therefore k_gas = constant, and P = k_gas/V, giving PV = k_gas = constant. This is Boyle's Law: at constant T, PV is constant. Gay-Lussac's Law: if volume is constant (V = constant), then P = (1/3)(N/V)m⟨v²⟩ = C × ⟨v²⟩, where C is constant. Since ½m⟨v²⟩ = (3/2)k_BT, we have ⟨v²⟩ = 3k_BT/m ∝ T. Therefore P ∝ T, which is Gay-Lussac's Law: at constant V, P is proportional to absolute temperature. Both laws emerge from the same single expression — confirming that the kinetic molecular theory unifies all three gas laws."
