                answer: "M(²³⁵UF₆) = 235 + 6×19 = 235 + 114 = 349 g/mol. M(²³⁸UF₆) = 238 + 114 = 352 g/mol. Enrichment factor per stage = √(352/349) = √1.00859 = 1.00428. Each stage enriches the ²³⁵U fraction by only 0.43% per pass. Natural uranium contains 0.72% ²³⁵U; weapons-grade uranium requires >90% ²³⁵U. The required number of stages n satisfies 0.0072 × (1.00428)ⁿ ≈ 0.90. Solving: (1.00428)ⁿ = 125. n × ln(1.00428) = ln(125). n = 4.828/0.004271 ≈ 1130 stages (minimum, ideal enrichment). In practice, more than 4000 stages were used in the Oak Ridge gaseous diffusion plant due to engineering efficiency limits — requiring the largest industrial facility ever built at the time. This is why uranium enrichment by diffusion is enormously energy-intensive."
