                answer: "Graham's Law strictly applies to effusion through a tiny pinhole (smaller than the mean free path λ ≈ 70 nm), where molecules pass individually without collisions. For diffusion through a rubber latex membrane, several complicating factors apply: (1) Rubber membrane permeability depends on solubility and diffusivity of the gas in the rubber material — these are gas-specific properties unrelated to molecular speed. H₂ has relatively low solubility in rubber compared to some other gases. (2) The pore structure of rubber is not uniform tiny holes but a complex polymer network — diffusion through a polymer is governed by the solution-diffusion mechanism: gas dissolves in the rubber, diffuses through, and evaporates on the other side. Solubility in the polymer is independent of molecular mass. (3) The effective 'pore size' is larger than the mean free path in many rubbers — bulk flow (Knudsen diffusion vs viscous diffusion regime) changes the mass dependence. (4) Temperature effects on polymer flexibility can affect diffusivity. These factors mean that real membrane permeability does not follow Graham's Law precisely."
