                answer: "In effusion through a tiny hole into a vacuum, molecules travel in straight lines at their thermal speed — nothing impedes their path. The effusion rate reflects the average thermal speed v_mean = √(8RT/πM). In diffusion of gas A through gas B at the same total pressure, molecule A collides with B molecules frequently — on average after travelling only the mean free path λ_AB (typically 50–100 nm at atmospheric pressure). Each collision deflects molecule A's direction randomly. Instead of a straight path at speed v_mean, molecule A performs a random walk with step length λ_AB and step frequency v_mean/λ_AB. The net displacement per unit time is the diffusion coefficient D ≈ (1/3)v_mean × λ_AB — which is much smaller than v_mean × t for the same time t. For example, λ_AB ≈ 100 nm and v_mean ≈ 500 m/s: D ≈ (1/3) × 500 × 10⁻⁷ ≈ 1.7 × 10⁻⁵ m²/s. To diffuse 1 cm: t ≈ r²/(2D) = (0.01)²/(2 × 1.7 × 10⁻⁵) ≈ 2.9 s. But at free-space speed, 1 cm takes t = 0.01/500 = 20 μs — 145,000 times faster. Diffusion is orders of magnitude slower than free-space motion due to the tortuous random walk caused by intermolecular collisions."
