                hint: "Count the active degrees of freedom: 3 translational for monatomic; 3 translational + 2 rotational for diatomic. Vibrational modes are frozen out at room temperature.",
                answer: "Monatomic ideal gas (e.g. He, Ar): has only translational kinetic energy — 3 translational degrees of freedom (x, y, z). Each stores (1/2)RT per mole: U = 3 × (1/2)RT = (3/2)RT per mole. C_v = dU/dT = (3/2)R ≈ 12.5 J/mol·K. Diatomic ideal gas (e.g. N₂, O₂) at room temperature: has 3 translational + 2 rotational degrees of freedom. The two rotational degrees (rotation about two axes perpendicular to the bond — rotation about the bond axis itself has negligible moment of inertia and is quantum-mechanically frozen). Each degree stores (1/2)RT: U = 5 × (1/2)RT = (5/2)RT per mole. C_v = (5/2)R ≈ 20.8 J/mol·K. At high temperatures, vibrational modes (1 mode for a diatomic = 2 degrees of freedom, kinetic + potential) become active, increasing C_v toward (7/2)R ≈ 29.1 J/mol·K. At room temperature, the vibrational mode's energy gap (quantised vibration) is too large relative to k_BT, so it is frozen — quantum mechanics prevents it from being excited by thermal energy."
