                answer: "For a monatomic gas: C_v = (3/2)R; C_p = C_v + R = (5/2)R. γ = C_p/C_v = (5/2)R / (3/2)R = 5/3 ≈ 1.667. For a diatomic gas: C_v = (5/2)R; C_p = (7/2)R. γ = 7/5 = 1.4. Speed of sound: v_s = √(γP/ρ) = √(γRT/M), where M is molar mass. For air (diatomic, γ = 1.4, M = 0.029 kg/mol) at 20°C: v_s = √(1.4 × 8.314 × 293 / 0.029) = √(117,760/0.029) = √(4,060,690) ≈ 347 m/s. (Accepted value ≈ 343 m/s — close agreement.) For helium (γ = 5/3, M = 0.004 kg/mol) at 20°C: v_s = √(1.667 × 8.314 × 293 / 0.004) = √(4,053,460) ≈ 970 m/s. Helium carries sound approximately 2.8 times faster than air — explaining why breathing helium changes voice pitch (higher frequency harmonics resonate in the vocal tract at higher speed). The ratio C_p/C_v determines how adiabatic compression affects temperature in sound waves — γ > 1 means the gas heats up during compression, which stiffens it and increases sound speed."
