                answer: "Adiabatic expansion against a piston: the gas does work pushing the piston outward: W = P_gas × ΔV > 0. With Q = 0 (adiabatic): ΔU = −W < 0. Internal energy decreases. For an ideal gas, ΔU = n × C_v × ΔT, so ΔT < 0 — the gas cools. The kinetic energy of molecules is converted into work on the piston — molecules slow down as they push the piston, reducing temperature. Free Joule expansion into vacuum: P_external = 0 in the vacuum, so W = P_external × ΔV = 0. With Q = 0: ΔU = 0. Internal energy unchanged. For an ideal gas, ΔT = 0 — no cooling. Molecules move into a larger space without doing any work — they travel further between wall collisions (fewer collisions per second → lower pressure) but their individual speeds are unchanged. The key physical difference: in the piston expansion, molecules must 'climb against' the piston force, losing kinetic energy. In free expansion, there is nothing to push against — molecules accelerate freely into the vacuum and arrive at the far wall with the same speed they had when they left."
