question: "Calculate the mean free path of nitrogen molecules at atmospheric pressure (101 kPa) and at 1 Pa (near-vacuum), given d(N₂) = 3.7 × 10⁻¹⁰ m and T = 293 K. Comment on the significance of each value.",
hint: "λ = k_BT/(√2 × π × d² × P). Calculate for P = 101,325 Pa and P = 1 Pa.",
answer: "λ = k_BT/(√2 πd²P). k_B = 1.381 × 10⁻²³ J/K, T = 293 K, d = 3.7 × 10⁻¹⁰ m. Numerator: k_BT = 1.381 × 10⁻²³ × 293 = 4.047 × 10⁻²¹ J. Denominator term: √2 πd² = 1.4142 × π × (3.7 × 10⁻¹⁰)² = 1.4142 × π × 1.369 × 10⁻¹⁹ = 6.082 × 10⁻¹⁹ m². At atmospheric P = 101,325 Pa: λ = 4.047 × 10⁻²¹ / (6.082 × 10⁻¹⁹ × 101,325) = 4.047 × 10⁻²¹ / 6.163 × 10⁻¹⁴ = 6.57 × 10⁻⁸ m ≈ 66 nm. At P = 1 Pa: λ = 6.57 × 10⁻⁸ × (101,325/1) ≈ 6.66 × 10⁻³ m ≈ 6.7 mm. Significance: at atmospheric pressure, λ = 66 nm — smaller than the wavelength of visible light and 180× the molecular diameter. Molecules collide approximately 7 billion times per second. At 1 Pa (rough vacuum used in some industrial processes), λ ≈ 6.7 mm — larger than many vacuum device features. Molecules travel centimetres between collisions, enabling directed molecular flow. At 10⁻⁶ Pa (high vacuum), λ ≈ 67 m — molecules travel the length of a room without collision, enabling molecular beam experiments."
