answer: "For NH₃: M = 17 g/mol, v_mean = √(8RT/πM) = √(8 × 8.314 × 293/(π × 0.017)) = √(19,511/0.0534) = √365,370 ≈ 604 m/s. λ ≈ 70 nm = 7 × 10⁻⁸ m (using air-like value for approximation). Time per step: τ = λ/v_mean = 7 × 10⁻⁸/604 = 1.16 × 10⁻¹⁰ s. After N steps, mean square displacement: ⟨r²⟩ = N × λ². For r = 5 m: N = r²/λ² = 25/(7 × 10⁻⁸)² = 25/(4.9 × 10⁻¹⁵) = 5.1 × 10¹⁵ steps. Total time: t = N × τ = 5.1 × 10¹⁵ × 1.16 × 10⁻¹⁰ = 5.92 × 10⁵ s ≈ 6.8 days. By pure diffusion alone, NH₃ would take nearly a week to diffuse 5 m. This matches Clausius's calculation — explaining why pure diffusion is very slow. In practice, room air convection currents (turbulent mixing) transport the smell in seconds to minutes, far faster than pure molecular diffusion."
