question: "At very low pressure (λ >> tube diameter), the flow regime changes from viscous (many collisions between molecules) to molecular (few collisions between molecules). Describe the key difference in how gas behaves in each regime and give one technological application where the molecular flow regime is essential.",
hint: "In viscous flow, molecules collide frequently with each other before hitting the walls. In molecular flow, each molecule hits the walls without colliding with other molecules.",
answer: "Viscous flow regime (λ << tube diameter): gas molecules collide frequently with each other — the gas behaves as a continuous fluid with bulk properties (viscosity, pressure gradients). Molecules exchange momentum through intermolecular collisions, creating a flow profile (faster at the centre, slower near walls — Poiseuille flow). The flow rate depends on pressure difference and tube viscosity. Molecular flow regime (λ >> tube diameter): gas molecules travel from wall to wall without encountering other molecules. Each molecule moves independently in response to the wall geometry, not to pressure gradients. Gas 'flow' becomes a statistical problem of molecular trajectories bouncing off walls — described by the Knudsen number (Kn = λ/d > 1). Flow rate is independent of pressure difference and depends only on molecular speed and tube geometry. Technological application: thin-film deposition in semiconductor manufacturing. In physical vapour deposition (PVD) and sputtering, the vacuum chamber is at ~10⁻³ Pa where λ >> chamber dimensions. Material evaporated from a target travels in straight lines to the substrate without collisions — enabling precise, directional deposition of atomically thin films. Without molecular flow (low λ), collisions would scatter the deposited material randomly and prevent uniform thin-film formation. All modern semiconductor devices rely on this molecular flow regime for their manufacture."
