question: "The viscosity of a gas is approximately η ≈ (1/3) × ρ × v_mean × λ. Using λ ∝ 1/P and n ∝ P (so ρ = nm ∝ P), show that viscosity is independent of pressure. Explain the physical reason for this surprising result.",
hint: "Substitute λ ∝ 1/P and ρ ∝ P — what happens to their product?",
answer: "η ≈ (1/3) × ρ × v_mean × λ. At constant T: v_mean = √(8RT/πM) = constant (independent of P). ρ = nm ∝ n ∝ P (from ideal gas law at constant T). λ = k_BT/(√2 πd²P) ∝ 1/P. Product: ρ × λ ∝ P × (1/P) = constant. Therefore: η ≈ (1/3) × constant × v_mean = constant — viscosity is independent of pressure! This was predicted by Maxwell in 1860 and was highly counterintuitive — confirmed experimentally by himself and others. The physical reason: at higher pressure, there are more molecules (higher ρ), which tends to increase viscosity. But each molecule travels a shorter distance before colliding (smaller λ), which tends to decrease momentum transport per molecule. The two effects cancel exactly. This is only valid above the molecular flow regime (λ << container size) — at very low pressures where λ approaches the container dimensions, viscosity drops with pressure because molecules can no longer effectively transfer momentum across the container."
