answer: "At atmospheric pressure (101,325 Pa), λ_atm ≈ 70 nm = 7 × 10⁻⁸ m. Since λ ∝ 1/P: P = λ_atm × P_atm / λ_target = (7 × 10⁻⁸ × 101,325) / (7 × 10⁻⁵) = 7090 / 7 × 10⁻⁵ = 101.3 Pa ≈ 0.001 atm. At approximately 100 Pa (about 1 millibar), the mean free path equals the diameter of a human hair. In a tube of this width at this pressure, the Knudsen number Kn = λ/d_tube = 70 μm / 70 μm = 1 — this is the transition regime between viscous and molecular flow. At Kn = 1, neither the continuous fluid approximation nor the pure molecular flow model is accurate. For Kn > 1 (λ > tube diameter), molecular flow dominates — molecules are more likely to hit the tube walls than each other. This transition regime (0.001 < Kn < 1) requires the Navier-Stokes equations to be modified with slip boundary conditions. This regime is relevant for gas flow in microelectromechanical systems (MEMS), microfluidic devices, and nanoscale gas channels in modern technology."
